y|Prohibition]] nominee for [[President of the United States]]|years=[[1908 United States presidential election|1908]], [[1912 United States presidential election|1912]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Frank Hanly]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Prohibition Party presidential nominees}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chafin, Eugene W.}}\n[[Category:1852 births]]\n[[Category:1920 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths in California]]\n[[Category:Arizona Prohibitionists]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1908 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 1912 United States presidential election]]\n[[Category:Illinois Prohibitionists]]\n[[Category:People from East Troy, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Waukesha, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Prohibition Party (United States) presidential nominees]]\n[[Category:School board members in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:University of Wisconsin&ndash;Madison alumni]]\n[[Category:Wisconsin lawyers]]\n[[Category:Wisconsin Prohibitionists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Wisconsin]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eugene_W._Chafin"}
{"title_page": "Elsie Jury", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Elsie Jury|timestamp=20200414130308|year=2020|month=April|day=14|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Elsie Jury|date=14 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{short description|Canadian archaeologist}}\n{{Infobox academic\n|name              = Elsie Jury\n|image             =\n|birth_date        = 1910<ref>{{cite web |title=Elsie Jury: Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=http://archaeologymuseum.ca/elsie-jury/ |website=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |publisher=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>  \n|birth_place       = Perth, Ontario, Canada<ref>{{cite web |title=Elsie Jury: Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=http://archaeologymuseum.ca/elsie-jury/ |website=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |publisher=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>  \n|death_date        = {{death date and age|1993|3|31|1910|10|11}}\n|death_place       = Ontario, Ontario<ref>{{cite web |title=Elsie Jury: Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=http://archaeologymuseum.ca/elsie-jury/ |website=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |publisher=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>  \n|residence         = \n|citizenship       = \n|nationality       = Canadian\n|occupation        = Archaeologist, Historian, Author, and Archivist\n|spouse            = Wilfrid Jury<ref>{{cite web |title=Elsie Jury: Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=http://archaeologymuseum.ca/elsie-jury/ |website=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |publisher=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |title=Wilfrid Jury and the Museum of Indian Archaeology and Pioneer Life |url=https://tmhc.ca/digital-exhibits/lawson/lawson-site-jurys |website=Timmins Martelle Heritage Consultants Inc. |publisher=Timmins Martelle Heritage Consultants Inc. |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> \n|discipline        = [[Archaeology]]\n|ethnicity         = Irish and Scottish decent<ref>{{cite web |title=Elsie Jury: Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=http://archaeologymuseum.ca/elsie-jury/ |website=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |publisher=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> \n|field             = [[archaeology]]\n|work_institutions = Royal Ontario Museum], Ontario, Canada\n|alma_mater        = University of Toronto, Ontario, Canada<ref>{{cite web |title=Elsie Jury: Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=http://archaeologymuseum.ca/elsie-jury/ |website=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |publisher=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>   & Columbia University, New York City, NY, US<ref>{{cite web |title=Elsie Jury: Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=http://archaeologymuseum.ca/elsie-jury/ |website=Ontario Museum of Archaeology, London, Ontario |publisher=Ontario Museum of Archaeology, London, Ontario |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> \n|doctoral_advisor  = \n|doctoral_students = \n|known_for         = her role in excavations at Sainte-Marie among the Hurons, Ontario, in 1947. Helped establish Fanshawe Pioneer Village<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kanigan |first1=Joan |title=Elsie Jury Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=https://trowelblazers.com/elsie-jury/ |website=Trowelblazers |publisher=Trowelblazers |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> and the Museum of Ontario Archaeology<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kanigan |first1=Joan |title=Elsie Jury Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=https://trowelblazers.com/elsie-jury/ |website=Trowelblazers |publisher=Trowelblazers |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>.\n|influences        = \n|influenced        = Wilfrid Jury<ref>{{cite web |title=Elsie Jury: Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=http://archaeologymuseum.ca/elsie-jury/ |website=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |publisher=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>  \n|prizes            = \n|religion          = \n}}\n\n==Early Life and Education:==\nElsie McLeod Murray Jury was born in Perth, Ontario,<ref>{{cite web |title=Elsie Jury: Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=http://archaeologymuseum.ca/elsie-jury/ |website=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |publisher=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>   Canada in 1910<ref>{{cite web |title=Elsie Jury: Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=http://archaeologymuseum.ca/elsie-jury/ |website=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |publisher=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>. She attended University of Toronto for a degree where she specialised in History and English<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kanigan |first1=Joan |title=Elsie Jury Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=https://trowelblazers.com/elsie-jury/ |website=Trowelblazers |publisher=Trowelblazers |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> and graduated in 1933.<ref>{{cite web |title=Elsie Jury: Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=http://archaeologymuseum.ca/elsie-jury/ |website=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |publisher=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>. She subsequently studied for a MA at Columbia University in History<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kanigan |first1=Joan |title=Elsie Jury Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=https://trowelblazers.com/elsie-jury/ |website=Trowelblazers |publisher=Trowelblazers |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> and wrote her thesis on her Scottish ancestors who had settled in Perth County, Ontario<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kanigan |first1=Joan |title=Elsie Jury Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=https://trowelblazers.com/elsie-jury/ |website=Trowelblazers |publisher=Trowelblazers |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>. She was of Scottish and Irish descent and her parents had immigrated to Millbank, in Mornington Township, in Perth County, Ontario during the early 19th century.<ref>{{cite web |title=Elsie Jury: Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=http://archaeologymuseum.ca/elsie-jury/ |website=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |publisher=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>. Elsie's father was was a doctor while her mother had raised their family<ref>{{cite web |title=Elsie Jury: Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=http://archaeologymuseum.ca/elsie-jury/ |website=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |publisher=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==Sites Excavated:==\n* Ste. Marie, Ontario, Canada<ref>{{cite web |title=Wilfrid Jury and the Museum of Indian Archaeology and Pioneer Life |url=https://tmhc.ca/digital-exhibits/lawson/lawson-site-jurys |website=Timmins Martelle Heritage Consultants Inc. |publisher=Timmins Martelle Heritage Consultants Inc. |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> \n* Forget, Ontario, Canada<ref>{{cite web |title=Wilfrid Jury and the Museum of Indian Archaeology and Pioneer Life |url=https://tmhc.ca/digital-exhibits/lawson/lawson-site-jurys |website=Timmins Martelle Heritage Consultants Inc. |publisher=Timmins Martelle Heritage Consultants Inc. |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>  \n* Penetanguishene, Ontario, Canada<ref>{{cite web |title=Wilfrid Jury and the Museum of Indian Archaeology and Pioneer Life |url=https://tmhc.ca/digital-exhibits/lawson/lawson-site-jurys |website=Timmins Martelle Heritage Consultants Inc. |publisher=Timmins Martelle Heritage Consultants Inc. |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n==Publications:==\nSole Author:\n* Jury, Elsie McLoed Murry 1974 ''The Neutral Indians of Southwestern Ontario''. London: MIA, Bulletin 13 (Reprinted, 1977).\n\nJoint Author:\n* Jury, Wilfrid and Elsie M. Jury 1952 The Burly Site. ''Ontario History'' 44:57-75. \n* Jury, Wilfrid and Elsie M. Jury 1954 ''Sainte-Marie Among Hurons.'' Toronto: Oxford University Press. \n* Jury, Wilfrid and Elsie M. Jury 1955 ''Saint Louis: Huron Village and Jesuit Mission Site.'' London: MIA, Bulletin 10.\n\n==References:==\n\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Elsie Jury|timestamp=20200414130308|year=2020|month=April|day=14|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Elsie Jury|date=14 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{short description|Canadian archaeologist}}\n{{Infobox academic\n|name              = Elsie Jury\n|image             =\n|birth_date        = 1910<ref>{{cite web |title=Elsie Jury: Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=http://archaeologymuseum.ca/elsie-jury/ |website=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |publisher=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>  \n|birth_place       = Perth, Ontario, Canada<ref>{{cite web |title=Elsie Jury: Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=http://archaeologymuseum.ca/elsie-jury/ |website=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |publisher=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>  \n|death_date        = {{death date and age|1993|3|31|1910|10|11}}\n|death_place       = Ontario, Ontario<ref>{{cite web |title=Elsie Jury: Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=http://archaeologymuseum.ca/elsie-jury/ |website=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |publisher=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>  \n|residence         = \n|citizenship       = \n|nationality       = Canadian\n|occupation        = Archaeologist, Historian, Author, and Archivist\n|spouse            = Wilfrid Jury<ref>{{cite web |title=Elsie Jury: Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=http://archaeologymuseum.ca/elsie-jury/ |website=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |publisher=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |title=Wilfrid Jury and the Museum of Indian Archaeology and Pioneer Life |url=https://tmhc.ca/digital-exhibits/lawson/lawson-site-jurys |website=Timmins Martelle Heritage Consultants Inc. |publisher=Timmins Martelle Heritage Consultants Inc. |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> \n|discipline        = [[Archaeology]]\n|ethnicity         = Irish and Scottish decent<ref>{{cite web |title=Elsie Jury: Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=http://archaeologymuseum.ca/elsie-jury/ |website=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |publisher=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> \n|field             = [[archaeology]]\n|work_institutions = Royal Ontario Museum], Ontario, Canada\n|alma_mater        = University of Toronto, Ontario, Canada<ref>{{cite web |title=Elsie Jury: Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=http://archaeologymuseum.ca/elsie-jury/ |website=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |publisher=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>   & Columbia University, New York City, NY, US<ref>{{cite web |title=Elsie Jury: Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=http://archaeologymuseum.ca/elsie-jury/ |website=Ontario Museum of Archaeology, London, Ontario |publisher=Ontario Museum of Archaeology, London, Ontario |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> \n|doctoral_advisor  = \n|doctoral_students = \n|known_for         = her role in excavations at Sainte-Marie among the Hurons, Ontario, in 1947. Helped establish Fanshawe Pioneer Village<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kanigan |first1=Joan |title=Elsie Jury Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=https://trowelblazers.com/elsie-jury/ |website=Trowelblazers |publisher=Trowelblazers |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> and the Museum of Ontario Archaeology<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kanigan |first1=Joan |title=Elsie Jury Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=https://trowelblazers.com/elsie-jury/ |website=Trowelblazers |publisher=Trowelblazers |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>.\n|influences        = \n|influenced        = Wilfrid Jury<ref>{{cite web |title=Elsie Jury: Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=http://archaeologymuseum.ca/elsie-jury/ |website=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |publisher=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>  \n|prizes            = \n|religion          = \n}}\n\n==Early Life and Education:==\nElsie McLeod Murray Jury was born in Perth, Ontario,<ref>{{cite web |title=Elsie Jury: Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=http://archaeologymuseum.ca/elsie-jury/ |website=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |publisher=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>   Canada in 1910<ref>{{cite web |title=Elsie Jury: Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=http://archaeologymuseum.ca/elsie-jury/ |website=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |publisher=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>. She attended University of Toronto for a degree where she specialised in History and English<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kanigan |first1=Joan |title=Elsie Jury Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=https://trowelblazers.com/elsie-jury/ |website=Trowelblazers |publisher=Trowelblazers |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> and graduated in 1933.<ref>{{cite web |title=Elsie Jury: Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=http://archaeologymuseum.ca/elsie-jury/ |website=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |publisher=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>. She subsequently studied for a MA at Columbia University in History<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kanigan |first1=Joan |title=Elsie Jury Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=https://trowelblazers.com/elsie-jury/ |website=Trowelblazers |publisher=Trowelblazers |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> and wrote her thesis on her Scottish ancestors who had settled in Perth County, Ontario<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kanigan |first1=Joan |title=Elsie Jury Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=https://trowelblazers.com/elsie-jury/ |website=Trowelblazers |publisher=Trowelblazers |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>. She was of Scottish and Irish descent and her parents had immigrated to Millbank, in Mornington Township, in Perth County, Ontario during the early 19th century.<ref>{{cite web |title=Elsie Jury: Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=http://archaeologymuseum.ca/elsie-jury/ |website=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |publisher=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>. Elsie's father was was a doctor while her mother had raised their family<ref>{{cite web |title=Elsie Jury: Pioneering Local Archaeology |url=http://archaeologymuseum.ca/elsie-jury/ |website=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |publisher=Museum of Ontario Archaeology |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\n==Sites Excavated:==\n* Ste. Marie, Ontario, Canada<ref>{{cite web |title=Wilfrid Jury and the Museum of Indian Archaeology and Pioneer Life |url=https://tmhc.ca/digital-exhibits/lawson/lawson-site-jurys |website=Timmins Martelle Heritage Consultants Inc. |publisher=Timmins Martelle Heritage Consultants Inc. |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> \n* Forget, Ontario, Canada<ref>{{cite web |title=Wilfrid Jury and the Museum of Indian Archaeology and Pioneer Life |url=https://tmhc.ca/digital-exhibits/lawson/lawson-site-jurys |website=Timmins Martelle Heritage Consultants Inc. |publisher=Timmins Martelle Heritage Consultants Inc. |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>  \n* Penetanguishene, Ontario, Canada<ref>{{cite web |title=Wilfrid Jury and the Museum of Indian Archaeology and Pioneer Life |url=https://tmhc.ca/digital-exhibits/lawson/lawson-site-jurys |website=Timmins Martelle Heritage Consultants Inc. |publisher=Timmins Martelle Heritage Consultants Inc. |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n==Publications:==\nSole Author:\n* Jury, Elsie 1974 ''The Neutral Indians of Southwestern Ontario''. London: MIA, Bulletin 13 (Reprinted, 1977).\nJoint Author:\n* Jury, Wilfrid and Elsie M. Jury 1952 The Burly Site. ''Ontario History'' 44:57-75. \n* Jury, Wilfrid and Elsie M. Jury 1954 ''Sainte-Marie Among Hurons.'' Toronto: Oxford University Press. \n* Jury, Wilfrid and Elsie M. Jury 1955 ''Saint Louis: Huron Village and Jesuit Mission Site.'' London: MIA, Bulletin 10.\n\n==References:==\n\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "35winds", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePublications::added full reference", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elsie_Jury"}
{"title_page": "Bani Sakher", "text_new": "[[File:Sheikh Hadeetha Al-Khraisha of the Bani Sakhr Tribe.jpg|thumb|Sheikh [[Haditha Al-Khraisha]] of the Bani Sakhr Tribe]]\n'''Beni Sakhr''' is the name of a large [[Bedouin]] tribe living in [[Jordan]]. The Bani Sakhr migrated to central Jordan from the [[Hijaz]] in the late eighteenth century.<ref>Falconry in Arabia, Mark Allen; 1980, p.33.</ref> According to the 1986 Jordanian Electoral Law, the Bani Sakhr tribe is made up of fourteen clans: Al-Fayez; AL-Jahawsheh;Al-Khirshan; Al-Jbour; Al-Salim; Al-Badareen; Al-Gudah; Al-Hammad; Al-Shra'ah and Al-Zaben (traditionally known collectively as the Ka'abnah half of the Bani Sakhr); Al-Ghbein; Al-Amir; Al-Ka'abna; Al-Hgeish; Al-Saleet, and Al-Taybeen (traditionally known collectively as the Twaga half of the Bani Sakhr).<ref>{{cite book|last1=Muhammad|first1=Ghazi bin|title=The Tribes of Jordan at the Beginning of the Twenty-First Century|date=1999|url=http://rissc.jo/?option=com_content&view=article&id=275%3Athe-tribes-of-jordan-at-the-beginning-of-the-twenty-first-century-&catid=59%3Aturab--rutab-series&Itemid=84|page=10|edition=first|accessdate=16 May 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Al Faiz.jpg|thumb|right|Sheikh [[Mithqal Fayez|Mithqal Pasha Al-Fayez]], Jerusalem, 1933]]\n\n==Origin==\nThe Bani Sakhr was tribe title that was given to more than one tribe, but the greatest and most famous of its tribes that were are the sons of Sakhr Al-Ta\u2019yun from Bani [[Tayy]], who refer to their lineage to an offense of the famous [[Qahtanite|Qahtaniya tribe]]; specifically the [[Kahlan|Kahlani]] sub-group. The Tayy's lived in what is now the [[Ha'il Region]], where Sakhr Al-Ta'yun and the now Bani Sakhr mainly lived on top of the \"Mountain of Lions\".{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nThen the Bani Sakhr migrated to occupy the lands [[Tayma]] to [[Al-\u02bfUla|Al-Ula]]; where they were adjacent to the [[Harb tribe|Bani Harb]] which led to the mixing of the two tribes. including some genealogists to fall into error and consider the tribe of Bani Sakhr a part of [[Harb tribe|Bani Harb]]. The Bani Sakhr were also adjacent to [[Anazzah|Bani Anazzah]], whom inhabited the [[Khaybar|Khayber]], and between the two tribes there were several conflicts, including the orientalist [[Frederick Peake|Frederick Gerard Peake]] in his book \"''A History of Jordan and its Tribes'', x, 1958\" that the tribe of Bani Sakhr clashed with tribes of Anazzah on the way to migrate to the [[Levant]]. The battle ended with the Anazzah's defeat, forcing some of their sub-groups to migrate to the northern more, and this explains the hostility between the two tribes.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nIn Frederick's book, he also documented the clash between Bani Sakhr and the [[Al-Dhafeer|Al-Dhafeer tribes]] and that they defeated [[Al-Dhafeer]]. However, Al-Dhafeer regrouped again under the leadership of their knight Sultan Ibn Suwit, and followed Bani Sakhr, whom where heading heading north of the Arabian Peninsula. The two tribes met again in Wadi Azraq, now known as [[Azraq, Jordan|Azraq]], on the Saudi-Jordanian border. Banu Sakhr was able once again to defeat the tribes of Al-Dhafeer, killing Sheikh Sultan Ibn Suwit where he lies in his tomb in that region next to a water ravine the was named after him (Ghadeer Sultan).{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nBani Sakhr then headed towards [[Balqa Governorate|Al-Balqa]] however their stay did not last long because the tribes didn't welcome them, most notably the [[:ar:\u0639\u062f\u0648\u0627\u0646_(\u0642\u0628\u064a\u0644\u0629)|Al-Adwan (\u0627\u0644\u0639\u062f\u0648\u0627\u0646)]] whom where extending their influence over the region. Bani Sakhr went to Palestine and stayed for a period of time until it soon returned to Al-Balqa. At this time, the area was under the sovereignty of the Sardiyya tribe, which was imposing a tax on the tribes that inhabited the areas in and around Al-Balqa, however when the Bani Sakhr returned, they refused to get taxed, which led to a heated situation between them.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nThis conflict lead to the first alliance between Bani Sakhr and Al-Adwan where they joined forces with the intent to annihilate the Sardiyya tribe.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Background==\nIn the 1799 the Beni Sakhr joined the Es-Sabhah and other tribes in a full-scale [[Battle of Mount Tabor (1799)|battle]] against a force from [[Napoleon]]'s army under the command of [[General Kleber]]. The fighting occurred south of [[Nazareth]], with the French having such an advantage in terms of guns and artillery that Amir Rabah, the leader of the Beni Saqr, commenting on the effectiveness of his spear, said that he \"could not swim in hell with a stick.\"<ref>Macalister and Masterman, 1906, p. [https://archive.org/stream/quarterlystateme38pale#page/114/mode/1up 114].</ref>\n\nIn the 19th century, the Beni Sakhr lived as nomads. Their income came from trading [[camel]]s and from the protection they could give, or refuse to give, to more settled peoples. In 1867, the [[Ottoman Empire]] launched a raid which defeated the Beni Sakhr and ended their practice of collecting ''khuwwa'' (protection money) from established settlements.\n\nFor fifty years up to 1920 the Bani Sakhr were friends and allies of the [[Rashidi dynasty|Al Rashid]] dynasty. The relationship ended with [[Ibn Saud]]'s conquest of the [[Nejd]]. It had its roots in the early nineteenth century when Abdullah Ibn Rashid was fleeing the Ibn Ali family after a conflict over leadership of the [[Shammar]] tribe. Ibn Rashid and his brother with a single camel arrived at the tents belonging to [[Haditha Al-Khraisha|Ali Al-Khraisha]], leader of the Beni Sakhr and father of [[Haditha Al-Khraisha]]. Sheikh [[Haditha Al-Khraisha|Ali Al-Khraisha]] was not there but all the same they were given hospitality. During the night the camel died and the next day they continued their flight on foot. Some distance from the camp they met Sheikh [[Haditha Al-Khraisha|Ali Al-Khraisha]] returning home. On hearing their story he insisted on them taking the camel he was riding, claiming that no guest who came into his camp riding should leave on foot. When Ibn Rashid came to power in the Nejd this deed was remembered.<ref>Glubb, 1978, pp. [https://archive.org/details/arabianadventure0000glub/page/157 157]-8.</ref>\n\nIn 1875 a member of the [[Palestine Exploration Fund]]'s survey team reported finding the Beni Sakhr in the [[Jordan Valley (Middle East)|Ghor]], a considerable extent of which was under cultivation. They had several herds containing 100 to 300 head of cattle and many sheep and goats as well as camels and horses. He mentions that they had fewer camels than previously since their power had been broken 7 or 8 years earlier by Mohammed Said, Pasha of [[Nablus]], but that the current government was impotent. He counted 150 tents and estimated the tribe strength as 400 men.<ref>Tyrwhitt Drake, 1875, pp. [https://archive.org/stream/quarterlystateme07pale#page/n37/mode/1up 28], [https://archive.org/stream/quarterlystateme07pale#page/n41/mode/1up 32]</ref>\n\nTwo years later, 1877, the survey team led by Lieutenant [[Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener|Kitchener]], found the Bani Sakhr camped on the road to [[Jenin]], and later between [[Beisan]] and [[Tiberias]]. Kitchener reported that their Sheikh, Fendy Alfayez, was the most powerful local leader and could muster 4,500 fighting men. The sheikh showed Kitchener a coat of mail that probably dated to the early centuries of the Arab conquests and appeared to be on good terms with the government. The tribe showed no sign of lawlessness, though local farmers had to harvest their crops early to avoid them being eaten by the grazing camels. The Beni Sakhr showed no interest in the ongoing war in the [[Russo-Turkish War (1877\u20131878)|Balkans]] and expressed a strong dislike of the [[Ottoman Empire|Turks]].<ref>Kitchener, 1877, p. [https://archive.org/stream/quarterlystateme09pale#page/n179/mode/1up 164]; Kitchener, 1878, p. [https://archive.org/stream/quarterlystateme09pale#page/11/mode/1up 11]; Reports dated 23 August and 7 September 1877.</ref>\n\nIn November 1877 Kitchener visited the Beni Sakhr again. This time they were camped in [[Wadi al-Far'a|Wadi Farrah]] having left the area around [[Zir'in|Zerin]] in the [[Jezreel Valley]] following the murder near [[Nazareth]] of a British man, Mr Gale, about which they had come under suspicion. Sheikh Fendy was absent at [[Bosra]] selling camel to pilgrims on the [[Haj]]. The Beni Sakhr were close to having a monopoly in this trade and could make \u00a31,500 in a season. Whilst in Bosra the sheikh was arrested. His son was killed in a rescue attempt. The father was released and is reported as having said \"My son and I were servants of the Sultan, now he has one less\". This was taken to mean that the tribe would not engage in a blood feud.<ref>Kitchener, 1878, p. [https://archive.org/stream/quarterlystateme09pale#page/63/mode/1up 63]</ref>\n\nIn 1891 missionaries reported fighting north of [[Al Karak|Kerak]] between the Beni Sakhr and the [[Bani Hamida|Hameidah]]. And again in 1893 the route between Kerak and [[Madaba]] was closed due to fighting between the Beni Sakhr and the [[`Anizzah|Anazi]].<ref>Forder, 1902, pp. [https://archive.org/stream/cu31924095645416#page/n39/mode/1up 16], [https://archive.org/stream/cu31924095645416#page/n50/mode/1up 27]</ref>\n\nIn June 1917 Fawaz el Fayez, one of the leaders of the Bani Sakhr, had a secret meeting with [[T.E. Lawrence]]. El Fayez was a member of an anti-Turkish committee in [[Damascus]] and Lawrence was seeking support for his military campaign. Immediately after the meeting Lawrence fled fearing betrayal. El Fayez was killed shortly afterwards. By June 1918 the Bani Sakhr were united in their opposition to the Turks and were offering to provide the Husseini forces with at least eleven thousand men costing \u00a330,000(\u00a31,715,944.76 adjusted to inflation as of April,2020) a month. In addition they would donate the harvest of [[Kerak]] and [[Madeba]].<ref>Wilson, Jeremy (1989) ''Lawrence of Arabia: the authorised biography of T.E.Lawrence.'' Heinemann. {{ISBN|0-434-87235-0}}. Pages 415, 515. The figure of 11,000 comes from a report by Lawrence.</ref>\n\nIn 1923 Ibn Saud's [[Ikhwan]] [[Ikhwan]] initiated their first attack on the [[Emirate of Transjordan]] by massacring two villages 12 miles south of Amman belonging to the tribe of Bani Sakhr. In a two-day battle, the tribesmen of Bani Sakhr assisted by the Hadid tribe managed to defeat the raiders.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P4cjDhBXV-4C&q=wahhabi#v=onepage&q=wahhabi&f=false|title=The Making of Jordan: Tribes, Colonialism and the Modern State|accessdate=2016-05-20|date=2007-04-15|author=Joab B. Eilon, Yoav Alon|publisher=I.B.Tauris}}</ref> The raiders were intercepted by British armored cars and planes only after they had begun to withdraw.<ref name=wilson143>Peter W. Wilson, Douglas Graham. ''Saudi Arabia: the coming storm ''. M.E.Sharpe, 1994: p.143</ref>\n<ref>Glubb, 1978, p. [https://archive.org/details/arabianadventure0000glub/page/156 156]</ref>\n\nOn 8 April 1933 Sheikh [[Mithqal Fayez|Mithqal Pasha al-Fayez]], Chief of the [[Fayez clan]] of Beni Sakhr, was a member of a delegation which met the President of the [[Zionist Organisation]], [[Chaim Weizmann]], and the head of the Zionist political department in Palestine, [[Chaim Arlosoroff]], at the [[King David Hotel]] in Jerusalem.<ref>Cohen, Aharon (1970) ''Israel and the Arab World.'' W.H. Allen. {{ISBN|0-491-00003-0}}. Pages 252-255.</ref>\n\nA series of events in the 1920s and 1930s put further pressure on their nomadic lifestyle, eventually leading to famine. The Bani Sakhr were saved from this by the [[United Kingdom|British]] government ruling Jordan at the time. In exchange, the British required the Bani Sakhr to give up their nomadic lifestyle and turned more towards a semi-nomadic life. In the decades since then, pressures on the Bani Sakhr to give up part of their land have led to occasional tension between them and the Jordanian government. However, this tribe has always been counted as stalwart allies of the Hashemite ruling family since the days of [[King Abdullah I]].<ref>http://landandpeople.blogspot.com/2007/09/baduw.html</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite journal | first = Archibald|last=Forder | title = With the Arabs in tent and town; an account of missionary work, life, and experiences in Moab and Edom, and the first missionary journey into Arabia from the north| url = https://archive.org/details/cu31924095645416|edition=3 |publisher=Marshall Brothers|location=London| year = 1902}} \n*{{cite journal | first = John|last=Glubb | authorlink1= John Glubb| title = Arabian Adventures. Ten years of joyful service | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=HlivAAAAIAAJ|publisher=Cassel | year = 1978|isbn=0-304-30171-X}} \n*{{cite journal |last1=Kitchener|first1=H. H.|authorlink1=Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener| title =Journal of the Survey| journal = Quarterly statement - Palestine Exploration Fund | volume = 9 | pages = 162\u2013164 | url = https://archive.org/details/quarterlystateme09pale | year = 1877}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Kitchener|first1=H. H.|authorlink1=Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener| title = Lieut.  Kitchener\u00b4s report| journal = Quarterly statement - Palestine Exploration Fund | volume = 10 | pages = 11\u201314 | url = https://archive.org/details/quarterlystateme09pale | year = 1878}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Kitchener|first1=H. H.|authorlink1=Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener| title =Journal of the Survey| journal = Quarterly statement - Palestine Exploration Fund | volume = 10 | pages = 62\u201367 | url = https://archive.org/details/quarterlystateme09pale | year = 1878}}\n*{{cite journal | author1 = Macalister, R. A. Stewart | author2 = Masterman, E. W. G. | authorlink1=  R. A. Stewart Macalister| title = Occasional Papers on the Modern inhabitants of Palestine, part VI | journal = Quarterly statement - Palestine Exploration Fund | volume = 38 | pages = 110\u2013114 | url = https://archive.org/details/quarterlystateme38pale | year = 1906}} \n*{{cite journal | author1 =Tyrwhitt Drake, C.F.| authorlink1 =Charles Francis Tyrwhitt-Drake| title = Mr Tyrwhitt Drake\u00b4s report | journal = Quarterly statement - Palestine Exploration Fund | volume = 7 | pages = 27\u201334 | url = https://archive.org/details/quarterlystateme38pale | year = 1875}} \n{{refend}}\n\n[[Category:Tribes of Arabia]]\n[[Category:Tribes of Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Bedouin groups]]\n[[Category:Tribes of Jordan]]\n<!-- start of StopAd injection -->\n\n<!-- end of StopAd injection -->\n", "text_old": "[[File:Sheikh Hadeetha Al-Khraisha of the Bani Sakhr Tribe.jpg|thumb|Sheikh [[Haditha Al-Khraisha]] of the Bani Sakhr Tribe]]\n'''Beni Sakhr''' is the name of a large [[Bedouin]] tribe living in [[Jordan]]. The Bani Sakhr migrated to central Jordan from the [[Hijaz]] in the late eighteenth century.<ref>Falconry in Arabia, Mark Allen; 1980, p.33.</ref> According to the 1986 Jordanian Electoral Law, the Bani Sakhr tribe is made up of fourteen clans: Al-Fayez; AL-Jahawsheh;Al-Khirshan; Al-Jbour; Al-Salim; Al-Badareen; Al-Gudah; Al-Hammad; Al-Shra'ah and Al-Zaben (traditionally known collectively as the Ka'abnah half of the Bani Sakhr); Al-Ghbein; Al-Amir; Al-Ka'abna; Al-Hgeish; Al-Saleet, and Al-Taybeen (traditionally known collectively as the Twaga half of the Bani Sakhr).<ref>{{cite book|last1=Muhammad|first1=Ghazi bin|title=The Tribes of Jordan at the Beginning of the Twenty-First Century|date=1999|url=http://rissc.jo/?option=com_content&view=article&id=275%3Athe-tribes-of-jordan-at-the-beginning-of-the-twenty-first-century-&catid=59%3Aturab--rutab-series&Itemid=84|page=10|edition=first|accessdate=16 May 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Al Faiz.jpg|thumb|right|Sheikh [[Mithqal Fayez|Mithqal Pasha Al-Fayez]], Jerusalem, 1933]]\n\n==Origin==\nThe Bani Sakhr was tribe title that was given to more than one tribe, but the greatest and most famous of its tribes that were are the sons of Sakhr Al-Ta\u2019yun from Bani [[Tayy]], who refer to their lineage to an offense of the famous [[Qahtanite|Qahtaniya tribe]]; specifically the [[Kahlan|Kahlani]] sub-group. The Tayy's lived in what is now the [[Ha'il Region]], where Sakhr Al-Ta'yun and the now Bani Sakhr mainly lived on top of the \"Mountain of Lions\".{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nThen the Bani Sakhr migrated to occupy the lands [[Tayma]] to [[Al-\u02bfUla|Al-Ula]]; where they were adjacent to the [[Harb|Bani Harb]] which led to the mixing of the two tribes. including some genealogists to fall into error and consider the tribe of Bani Sakhr a part of [[Harb|Bani Harb]]. The Bani Sakhr were also adjacent to [[Anazzah|Bani Anazzah]], whom inhabited the [[Khaybar|Khayber]], and between the two tribes there were several conflicts, including the orientalist [[Frederick Peake|Frederick Gerard Peake]] in his book \"''A History of Jordan and its Tribes'', x, 1958\" that the tribe of Bani Sakhr clashed with tribes of Anazzah on the way to migrate to the [[Levant]]. The battle ended with the Anazzah's defeat, forcing some of their sub-groups to migrate to the northern more, and this explains the hostility between the two tribes.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nIn Frederick's book, he also documented the clash between Bani Sakhr and the [[Al-Dhafeer|Al-Dhafeer tribes]] and that they defeated [[Al-Dhafeer]]. However, Al-Dhafeer regrouped again under the leadership of their knight Sultan Ibn Suwit, and followed Bani Sakhr, whom where heading heading north of the Arabian Peninsula. The two tribes met again in Wadi Azraq, now known as [[Azraq, Jordan|Azraq]], on the Saudi-Jordanian border. Banu Sakhr was able once again to defeat the tribes of Al-Dhafeer, killing Sheikh Sultan Ibn Suwit where he lies in his tomb in that region next to a water ravine the was named after him (Ghadeer Sultan).{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nBani Sakhr then headed towards [[Balqa Governorate|Al-Balqa]] however their stay did not last long because the tribes didn't welcome them, most notably the [[:ar:\u0639\u062f\u0648\u0627\u0646_(\u0642\u0628\u064a\u0644\u0629)|Al-Adwan (\u0627\u0644\u0639\u062f\u0648\u0627\u0646)]] whom where extending their influence over the region. Bani Sakhr went to Palestine and stayed for a period of time until it soon returned to Al-Balqa. At this time, the area was under the sovereignty of the Sardiyya tribe, which was imposing a tax on the tribes that inhabited the areas in and around Al-Balqa, however when the Bani Sakhr returned, they refused to get taxed, which led to a heated situation between them.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\nThis conflict lead to the first alliance between Bani Sakhr and Al-Adwan where they joined forces with the intent to annihilate the Sardiyya tribe.{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Background==\nIn the 1799 the Beni Sakhr joined the Es-Sabhah and other tribes in a full-scale [[Battle of Mount Tabor (1799)|battle]] against a force from [[Napoleon]]'s army under the command of [[General Kleber]]. The fighting occurred south of [[Nazareth]], with the French having such an advantage in terms of guns and artillery that Amir Rabah, the leader of the Beni Saqr, commenting on the effectiveness of his spear, said that he \"could not swim in hell with a stick.\"<ref>Macalister and Masterman, 1906, p. [https://archive.org/stream/quarterlystateme38pale#page/114/mode/1up 114].</ref>\n\nIn the 19th century, the Beni Sakhr lived as nomads. Their income came from trading [[camel]]s and from the protection they could give, or refuse to give, to more settled peoples. In 1867, the [[Ottoman Empire]] launched a raid which defeated the Beni Sakhr and ended their practice of collecting ''khuwwa'' (protection money) from established settlements.\n\nFor fifty years up to 1920 the Bani Sakhr were friends and allies of the [[Rashidi dynasty|Al Rashid]] dynasty. The relationship ended with [[Ibn Saud]]'s conquest of the [[Nejd]]. It had its roots in the early nineteenth century when Abdullah Ibn Rashid was fleeing the Ibn Ali family after a conflict over leadership of the [[Shammar]] tribe. Ibn Rashid and his brother with a single camel arrived at the tents belonging to [[Haditha Al-Khraisha|Ali Al-Khraisha]], leader of the Beni Sakhr and father of [[Haditha Al-Khraisha]]. Sheikh [[Haditha Al-Khraisha|Ali Al-Khraisha]] was not there but all the same they were given hospitality. During the night the camel died and the next day they continued their flight on foot. Some distance from the camp they met Sheikh [[Haditha Al-Khraisha|Ali Al-Khraisha]] returning home. On hearing their story he insisted on them taking the camel he was riding, claiming that no guest who came into his camp riding should leave on foot. When Ibn Rashid came to power in the Nejd this deed was remembered.<ref>Glubb, 1978, pp. [https://archive.org/details/arabianadventure0000glub/page/157 157]-8.</ref>\n\nIn 1875 a member of the [[Palestine Exploration Fund]]'s survey team reported finding the Beni Sakhr in the [[Jordan Valley (Middle East)|Ghor]], a considerable extent of which was under cultivation. They had several herds containing 100 to 300 head of cattle and many sheep and goats as well as camels and horses. He mentions that they had fewer camels than previously since their power had been broken 7 or 8 years earlier by Mohammed Said, Pasha of [[Nablus]], but that the current government was impotent. He counted 150 tents and estimated the tribe strength as 400 men.<ref>Tyrwhitt Drake, 1875, pp. [https://archive.org/stream/quarterlystateme07pale#page/n37/mode/1up 28], [https://archive.org/stream/quarterlystateme07pale#page/n41/mode/1up 32]</ref>\n\nTwo years later, 1877, the survey team led by Lieutenant [[Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener|Kitchener]], found the Bani Sakhr camped on the road to [[Jenin]], and later between [[Beisan]] and [[Tiberias]]. Kitchener reported that their Sheikh, Fendy Alfayez, was the most powerful local leader and could muster 4,500 fighting men. The sheikh showed Kitchener a coat of mail that probably dated to the early centuries of the Arab conquests and appeared to be on good terms with the government. The tribe showed no sign of lawlessness, though local farmers had to harvest their crops early to avoid them being eaten by the grazing camels. The Beni Sakhr showed no interest in the ongoing war in the [[Russo-Turkish War (1877\u20131878)|Balkans]] and expressed a strong dislike of the [[Ottoman Empire|Turks]].<ref>Kitchener, 1877, p. [https://archive.org/stream/quarterlystateme09pale#page/n179/mode/1up 164]; Kitchener, 1878, p. [https://archive.org/stream/quarterlystateme09pale#page/11/mode/1up 11]; Reports dated 23 August and 7 September 1877.</ref>\n\nIn November 1877 Kitchener visited the Beni Sakhr again. This time they were camped in [[Wadi al-Far'a|Wadi Farrah]] having left the area around [[Zir'in|Zerin]] in the [[Jezreel Valley]] following the murder near [[Nazareth]] of a British man, Mr Gale, about which they had come under suspicion. Sheikh Fendy was absent at [[Bosra]] selling camel to pilgrims on the [[Haj]]. The Beni Sakhr were close to having a monopoly in this trade and could make \u00a31,500 in a season. Whilst in Bosra the sheikh was arrested. His son was killed in a rescue attempt. The father was released and is reported as having said \"My son and I were servants of the Sultan, now he has one less\". This was taken to mean that the tribe would not engage in a blood feud.<ref>Kitchener, 1878, p. [https://archive.org/stream/quarterlystateme09pale#page/63/mode/1up 63]</ref>\n\nIn 1891 missionaries reported fighting north of [[Al Karak|Kerak]] between the Beni Sakhr and the [[Bani Hamida|Hameidah]]. And again in 1893 the route between Kerak and [[Madaba]] was closed due to fighting between the Beni Sakhr and the [[`Anizzah|Anazi]].<ref>Forder, 1902, pp. [https://archive.org/stream/cu31924095645416#page/n39/mode/1up 16], [https://archive.org/stream/cu31924095645416#page/n50/mode/1up 27]</ref>\n\nIn June 1917 Fawaz el Fayez, one of the leaders of the Bani Sakhr, had a secret meeting with [[T.E. Lawrence]]. El Fayez was a member of an anti-Turkish committee in [[Damascus]] and Lawrence was seeking support for his military campaign. Immediately after the meeting Lawrence fled fearing betrayal. El Fayez was killed shortly afterwards. By June 1918 the Bani Sakhr were united in their opposition to the Turks and were offering to provide the Husseini forces with at least eleven thousand men costing \u00a330,000(\u00a31,715,944.76 adjusted to inflation as of April,2020) a month. In addition they would donate the harvest of [[Kerak]] and [[Madeba]].<ref>Wilson, Jeremy (1989) ''Lawrence of Arabia: the authorised biography of T.E.Lawrence.'' Heinemann. {{ISBN|0-434-87235-0}}. Pages 415, 515. The figure of 11,000 comes from a report by Lawrence.</ref>\n\nIn 1923 Ibn Saud's [[Ikhwan]] [[Ikhwan]] initiated their first attack on the [[Emirate of Transjordan]] by massacring two villages 12 miles south of Amman belonging to the tribe of Bani Sakhr. In a two-day battle, the tribesmen of Bani Sakhr assisted by the Hadid tribe managed to defeat the raiders.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P4cjDhBXV-4C&q=wahhabi#v=onepage&q=wahhabi&f=false|title=The Making of Jordan: Tribes, Colonialism and the Modern State|accessdate=2016-05-20|date=2007-04-15|author=Joab B. Eilon, Yoav Alon|publisher=I.B.Tauris}}</ref> The raiders were intercepted by British armored cars and planes only after they had begun to withdraw.<ref name=wilson143>Peter W. Wilson, Douglas Graham. ''Saudi Arabia: the coming storm ''. M.E.Sharpe, 1994: p.143</ref>\n<ref>Glubb, 1978, p. [https://archive.org/details/arabianadventure0000glub/page/156 156]</ref>\n\nOn 8 April 1933 Sheikh [[Mithqal Fayez|Mithqal Pasha al-Fayez]], Chief of the [[Fayez clan]] of Beni Sakhr, was a member of a delegation which met the President of the [[Zionist Organisation]], [[Chaim Weizmann]], and the head of the Zionist political department in Palestine, [[Chaim Arlosoroff]], at the [[King David Hotel]] in Jerusalem.<ref>Cohen, Aharon (1970) ''Israel and the Arab World.'' W.H. Allen. {{ISBN|0-491-00003-0}}. Pages 252-255.</ref>\n\nA series of events in the 1920s and 1930s put further pressure on their nomadic lifestyle, eventually leading to famine. The Bani Sakhr were saved from this by the [[United Kingdom|British]] government ruling Jordan at the time. In exchange, the British required the Bani Sakhr to give up their nomadic lifestyle and turned more towards a semi-nomadic life. In the decades since then, pressures on the Bani Sakhr to give up part of their land have led to occasional tension between them and the Jordanian government. However, this tribe has always been counted as stalwart allies of the Hashemite ruling family since the days of [[King Abdullah I]].<ref>http://landandpeople.blogspot.com/2007/09/baduw.html</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite journal | first = Archibald|last=Forder | title = With the Arabs in tent and town; an account of missionary work, life, and experiences in Moab and Edom, and the first missionary journey into Arabia from the north| url = https://archive.org/details/cu31924095645416|edition=3 |publisher=Marshall Brothers|location=London| year = 1902}} \n*{{cite journal | first = John|last=Glubb | authorlink1= John Glubb| title = Arabian Adventures. Ten years of joyful service | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=HlivAAAAIAAJ|publisher=Cassel | year = 1978|isbn=0-304-30171-X}} \n*{{cite journal |last1=Kitchener|first1=H. H.|authorlink1=Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener| title =Journal of the Survey| journal = Quarterly statement - Palestine Exploration Fund | volume = 9 | pages = 162\u2013164 | url = https://archive.org/details/quarterlystateme09pale | year = 1877}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Kitchener|first1=H. H.|authorlink1=Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener| title = Lieut.  Kitchener\u00b4s report| journal = Quarterly statement - Palestine Exploration Fund | volume = 10 | pages = 11\u201314 | url = https://archive.org/details/quarterlystateme09pale | year = 1878}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Kitchener|first1=H. H.|authorlink1=Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener| title =Journal of the Survey| journal = Quarterly statement - Palestine Exploration Fund | volume = 10 | pages = 62\u201367 | url = https://archive.org/details/quarterlystateme09pale | year = 1878}}\n*{{cite journal | author1 = Macalister, R. A. Stewart | author2 = Masterman, E. W. G. | authorlink1=  R. A. Stewart Macalister| title = Occasional Papers on the Modern inhabitants of Palestine, part VI | journal = Quarterly statement - Palestine Exploration Fund | volume = 38 | pages = 110\u2013114 | url = https://archive.org/details/quarterlystateme38pale | year = 1906}} \n*{{cite journal | author1 =Tyrwhitt Drake, C.F.| authorlink1 =Charles Francis Tyrwhitt-Drake| title = Mr Tyrwhitt Drake\u00b4s report | journal = Quarterly statement - Palestine Exploration Fund | volume = 7 | pages = 27\u201334 | url = https://archive.org/details/quarterlystateme38pale | year = 1875}} \n{{refend}}\n\n[[Category:Tribes of Arabia]]\n[[Category:Tribes of Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Bedouin groups]]\n[[Category:Tribes of Jordan]]\n<!-- start of StopAd injection -->\n\n<!-- end of StopAd injection -->\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toHarb(link changed toHarb tribe; link changed toHarb tribe) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bani_Sakher"}
{"title_page": "Frances Theodora Parsons", "text_new": "{{short description|American botanist}}\n''Frances Parsons redirects here, for those of a similar name, see [[Francis Parsons (disambiguation)]]''\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name                    = Frances Theodora Parsons\n| image                   = Frances Theodora Parsons.png\n| image_size              = 240px\n| caption                 = \n| birth_date              = {{Birth date|1861|12|05}}\n| birth_place             = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| death_date              = {{Death date and age|1952|06|10|1861|12|05}}\n| death_place             = [[Katonah, New York]]\n| nationality             = American\n| field                   = [[Botany]]\n| known_for               = wildflower guidebooks\n| author_abbreviation_bot = F.Parsons\n| author_abbreviation_zoo = \n}}\n'''Frances Theodora Parsons''' (December 5, 1861 \u2013 June 10, 1952), who initially published as '''Mrs. William Starr Dana''', was an American naturalist and author active in the United States during the late 19th and early 20th centuries. She wrote a number of books, including a popular guide to American wildflowers.\n\n==Early life and education==\nFrances Theodora Smith was born in New York in 1861 to Denton Smith, a tea merchant, and Harriet Shelton Smith.<ref name=cassandra/> She had a sister, Alice Josephine (1859\u20131909), who became an artist and later illustrated two of her books. She was educated privately at Miss Comstock\u2019s School. She is said to have gained her love of botany during summers spent with her grandparents in rural New York state.<ref name=sierra/>\n\nHer first husband, William Starr Dana, whom she married in 1884, was a naval officer. He died in an 1890 flu epidemic, and six years later she married James Russell Parsons, a politician in the state of [[New York (state)|New York]] and later a diplomat.<ref name=sierra/> They had a son, Russell and a daughter, Dorothea, who died as a toddler.<ref name=cassandra/> James himself died in 1902 in an automobile accident in Mexico City.<ref name=cassandra/>\n\nFollowing James's death, Parsons moved to New York City, where she was an active supporter of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] as well as the [[Progressive Party (United States, 1912)|Progressive Party]]. She served in various official capacities on party committees, and she managed [[Fiorello H. La Guardia]]'s successful campaign to become president of New York's Board of Aldermen.<ref name=cassandra/> She was also an advocate of [[women's suffrage]].<ref name=sierra/>\n\n==Career==\nFollowing the loss of her first husband, Parsons' sought solace in long walks with her friend the illustrator [[Marion Satterlee]].<ref name=cassandra/> These outings prompted her first and most important botanical work, ''How to Know the Wild Flowers'' (1893), which was the first [[field guide]] to [[North America]]n [[wildflower]]s.<ref name=sierra/> It was something of a sensation, the first printing selling out in five days.<ref name=sierra/> ''How to Know the Wild Flowers'' garnered favorable responses from [[Theodore Roosevelt]] and [[Rudyard Kipling]], among others.<ref name=sierra/> The work went through several editions in Parsons's lifetime and has remained in print into the 21st century. It was organized by flower colors and illustrated with 48 full-page color plates by [[Elsie Louise Shaw]] (missing from later editions) and 110 full-page black-and-white illustrations by Satterlee.\n\nParsons' second book, ''According to Season'' (1894), was a compendium of nature writing that she had previously published in ''The New York Tribune''.<ref name=cassandra/>\n\nHer third book, ''Plants and Their Children'' (1896), was intended for children and was listed as one of the 50 best children\u2019s books of its day.<ref name=cassandra/>\n\nIn 1899, Parsons published ''How to Know the Ferns'', a companion to her first guidebook. The writing of this book was largely prompted by her husband's financial difficulties.<ref name=cassandra/>\n\nAfter her fourth book, Parsons stopped writing for several decades. In 1952, at the age of 90, she published a memoir, ''Perchance Some Day''.<ref name=sierra/>\n\n==Books==\n[[File:How_to_Know_the_Ferns_7th_ed._Cover.jpg|thumb|right|Cover of ''How to Know the Ferns'' (7th ed)]]\n\n===Writing as Mrs. William Starr Dana===\n* ''How to Know the Wild Flowers'' (1893). New York: Charles Scribner's Son's. Illustrations by Marion Satterlee and (in 1st edition) Elsie Louise Shaw. Published under name Mrs. William Starr Dana\n* ''According to Season'' (1894). Illustrated by Elsie Louise Shaw.\n* ''Plants and Their Children'' (1896). Illustrations by Alice Josephine Smith.\n\n===Writing as Frances Theodora Parsons===\n* ''[[s:How to Know the Ferns (7th ed)|How to Know the Ferns]]'' (1899). Illustrated by Marion Satterlee and Alice Josephine Smith. The first printing by Toronto: The Publisher's Syndicate Limited; at least seven more printings, 1899-1925 by New York: Charles Scribner's Son's; at least two printings by New York: Dover Books; and one printing, 2005, by Kessinger Publishing.\n* ''Perchance Some Day'' (1951). Autobiography, privately printed.\n\n{{botanist|F.Parsons|Parsons, Frances}}\n\n== References==\n{{Reflist | refs=\n\n<ref name=sierra>[http://www.sierracollege.edu/ejournals/jscnhm/v6n1/parsons.html Frances Theodora Parsons (Mrs. Wm Starr Dana)], Sierra College Natural History Museum, Retrieved 14 August 2015</ref>\n\n<ref name=cassandra>[http://cassandraconsiders.blogspot.com/2010/09/frances-theodora-parsons-aka-mrs.html \"Frances Theodora Parsons (a.k.a., Mrs. William Starr Dana)\"]. ''Cassandra Considers All Things Bright and Beautiful'' (blog), Sept. 8, 2010. Accessed Dec. 4, 2015.</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikisource|Author:Frances Theodora Parsons|Frances Theodora Parsons}}\n* {{Gutenberg author | id=Parsons,+Frances+Theodora | name=Frances Theodora Parsons}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Frances Theodora Parsons}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |name=Mrs. William Starr Dana}}\n* [http://www.pawildflower.org/01_articles/Notes_2004_Q1.pdf ''Who is Mrs. William Starr Dana?''] by Mary Finger, accessed 4 May 2006.\n* [http://www.ipni.org/ipni/authorsearch?id=12725-1&query_type=by_id&output_format=object_view&back_page=authorsearch&ret_surname=Parsons&ret_isoCountry=&ret_abbreviation=&ret_forename= Listing on ipni.org], accessed 4 May 2006.\n* [http://www.gutenberg.org/files/11365/11365-h/11365-h.htm ''The Fern Lover's Companion]\u2014Project Gutenberg, has short biography, thumbnail photo of Parsons\n* [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/creator/8679 Works by Parsons]\u2014Biodiversity Heritage Library\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parsons, Frances}}\n[[Category:American botanists]]\n[[Category:American naturalists]]\n[[Category:American women botanists]]\n[[Category:1861 births]]\n[[Category:1952 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Katonah, New York]]\n[[Category:Scientists from New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American botanist}}\n''Frances Parsons redirects here, for those of a similar name, see [[Francis Parsons (disambiguation)]]''\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name                    = Frances Theodora Parsons\n| image                   = Frances Theodora Parsons.png\n| image_size              = 240px\n| caption                 = \n| birth_date              = {{Birth date|1861|12|05}}\n| birth_place             = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| death_date              = {{Death date and age|1952|06|10|1861|12|05}}\n| death_place             = [[Katonah, New York]]\n| nationality             = American\n| field                   = [[Botany]]\n| known_for               = wildflower guidebooks\n| author_abbreviation_bot = F.Parsons\n| author_abbreviation_zoo = \n}}\n'''Frances Theodora Parsons''' (December 5, 1861 \u2013 June 10, 1952), who initially published as '''Mrs. William Starr Dana''', was an American naturalist and author active in the United States during the late 19th and early 20th centuries. She wrote a number of books, including a very popular guide to American wildflowers.\n\n==Early life and education==\nFrances Theodora Smith was born in New York in 1861 to Denton Smith, a tea merchant, and Harriet Shelton Smith.<ref name=cassandra/> She had a sister, Alice Josephine (1859\u20131909), who became an artist and later illustrated two of her books. She was educated privately at Miss Comstock\u2019s School. She is said to have gained her love of botany during summers spent with her grandparents in rural New York state.<ref name=sierra/>\n\nHer first husband, William Starr Dana, whom she married in 1884, was a naval officer. He died in an 1890 flu epidemic, and six years later she married James Russell Parsons, a politician in the state of [[New York (state)|New York]] and later a diplomat.<ref name=sierra/> They had a son, Russell and a daughter, Dorothea, who died as a toddler.<ref name=cassandra/> James himself died in 1902 in an automobile accident in Mexico City.<ref name=cassandra/>\n\nFollowing James's death, Parsons moved to New York City, where she was an active supporter of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] as well as the [[Progressive Party (United States, 1912)|Progressive Party]]. She served in various official capacities on party committees, and she managed [[Fiorello H. La Guardia]]'s successful campaign to become president of New York's Board of Aldermen.<ref name=cassandra/> She was also an advocate of [[women's suffrage]].<ref name=sierra/>\n\n==Career==\nFollowing the loss of her first husband, Parsons' sought solace in long walks with her friend the illustrator [[Marion Satterlee]].<ref name=cassandra/> These outings prompted her first and most important botanical work, ''How to Know the Wild Flowers'' (1893), which was the first [[field guide]] to [[North America]]n [[wildflower]]s.<ref name=sierra/> It was something of a sensation, the first printing selling out in five days.<ref name=sierra/> ''How to Know the Wild Flowers'' garnered favorable responses from [[Theodore Roosevelt]] and [[Rudyard Kipling]], among others.<ref name=sierra/> The work went through several editions in Parsons's lifetime and has remained in print into the 21st century. It was organized by flower colors and illustrated with 48 full-page color plates by [[Elsie Louise Shaw]] (missing from later editions) and 110 full-page black-and-white illustrations by Satterlee.\n\nParsons' second book, ''According to Season'' (1894), was a compendium of nature writing that she had previously published in ''The New York Tribune''.<ref name=cassandra/>\n\nHer third book, ''Plants and Their Children'' (1896), was intended for children and was listed as one of the 50 best children\u2019s books of its day.<ref name=cassandra/>\n\nIn 1899, Parsons published ''How to Know the Ferns'', a companion to her first guidebook. The writing of this book was largely prompted by her husband's financial difficulties.<ref name=cassandra/>\n\nAfter her fourth book, Parsons stopped writing for several decades. In 1952, at the age of 90, she published a memoir, ''Perchance Some Day''.<ref name=sierra/>\n\n==Books==\n[[File:How_to_Know_the_Ferns_7th_ed._Cover.jpg|thumb|right|Cover of ''How to Know the Ferns'' (7th ed)]]\n\n===Writing as Mrs. William Starr Dana===\n* ''How to Know the Wild Flowers'' (1893). New York: Charles Scribner's Son's. Illustrations by Marion Satterlee and (in 1st edition) Elsie Louise Shaw. Published under name Mrs. William Starr Dana\n* ''According to Season'' (1894). Illustrated by Elsie Louise Shaw.\n* ''Plants and Their Children'' (1896). Illustrations by Alice Josephine Smith.\n\n===Writing as Frances Theodora Parsons===\n* ''[[s:How to Know the Ferns (7th ed)|How to Know the Ferns]]'' (1899). Illustrated by Marion Satterlee and Alice Josephine Smith. The first printing by Toronto: The Publisher's Syndicate Limited; at least seven more printings, 1899-1925 by New York: Charles Scribner's Son's; at least two printings by New York: Dover Books; and one printing, 2005, by Kessinger Publishing.\n* ''Perchance Some Day'' (1951). Autobiography, privately printed.\n\n{{botanist|F.Parsons|Parsons, Frances}}\n\n== References==\n{{Reflist | refs=\n\n<ref name=sierra>[http://www.sierracollege.edu/ejournals/jscnhm/v6n1/parsons.html Frances Theodora Parsons (Mrs. Wm Starr Dana)], Sierra College Natural History Museum, Retrieved 14 August 2015</ref>\n\n<ref name=cassandra>[http://cassandraconsiders.blogspot.com/2010/09/frances-theodora-parsons-aka-mrs.html \"Frances Theodora Parsons (a.k.a., Mrs. William Starr Dana)\"]. ''Cassandra Considers All Things Bright and Beautiful'' (blog), Sept. 8, 2010. Accessed Dec. 4, 2015.</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikisource|Author:Frances Theodora Parsons|Frances Theodora Parsons}}\n* {{Gutenberg author | id=Parsons,+Frances+Theodora | name=Frances Theodora Parsons}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Frances Theodora Parsons}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |name=Mrs. William Starr Dana}}\n* [http://www.pawildflower.org/01_articles/Notes_2004_Q1.pdf ''Who is Mrs. William Starr Dana?''] by Mary Finger, accessed 4 May 2006.\n* [http://www.ipni.org/ipni/authorsearch?id=12725-1&query_type=by_id&output_format=object_view&back_page=authorsearch&ret_surname=Parsons&ret_isoCountry=&ret_abbreviation=&ret_forename= Listing on ipni.org], accessed 4 May 2006.\n* [http://www.gutenberg.org/files/11365/11365-h/11365-h.htm ''The Fern Lover's Companion]\u2014Project Gutenberg, has short biography, thumbnail photo of Parsons\n* [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/creator/8679 Works by Parsons]\u2014Biodiversity Heritage Library\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parsons, Frances}}\n[[Category:American botanists]]\n[[Category:American naturalists]]\n[[Category:American women botanists]]\n[[Category:1861 births]]\n[[Category:1952 deaths]]\n