{"title_page": "Maria van Pallaes", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Dutch philanthropist}}\n{{Dutch name|Van Pallaes|Pallaes}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = \n| name               = Maria van Pallaes\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = Maria van Pallaes, by Anthony Grolman, after Hendrick Bloemaert.jpg\n| caption            = 1878 painting of Van Pallaes, based on [[Hendrick Bloemaert]]'s portrait\n| pronunciation      = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth year|1587}}\n| birth_place        = [[Utrecht]], the Netherlands\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1664|10|23|1587|df=yes}}\n| death_place        = Utrecht\n| burial_place       = [[St. Martin's Cathedral, Utrecht|St. Martin's Cathedral]], Utrecht\n| burial_coordinates = {{coord|52|05|27|N|5|07|18|E|region:NL_type:landmark_source:nlwiki|display=inline}}\n| occupation         = \n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = [[Philanthropy]]\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Hendrick van Schroyesteijn|11 January 1606|1630|end=d}}\n| children           = 6\n}}\n\n'''Mayken Lubbert van Pallaesdr.'''{{refn|group=note|Bert Aanstoot refers to her full name with a [[full stop]] at the end,<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEAanstoot20155\" /> while M. Cornelis does not include a full stop.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTECornelis1996153\" />}} (1587 \u2013 23 October 1664), commonly known as '''Maria van Pallaes''',{{refn|group=note|{{IPA-nl|ma\u02d0ria\u02d0 van p\u0251l\u0251is}}}} was a Dutch [[Philanthropy|philanthropist]] who established the Maria van Pallaes houses in the city of [[Utrecht]]. They consist of 12 [[almshouse]]s and a [[refectory]], together with a {{lang|nl|[[hofje]]}} or courtyard garden, to be used by the city's [[Poverty|poor]]. After her death, the buildings were placed under the control of the Maria van Pallaes Foundation and another 28 almshouses were later built using her [[inheritance]]. The original 12 houses and refectory are now owned by the {{ill|Utrechts Monumentenfonds|lt=Utrecht Monument Foundation|nl||WD=}} and are a [[Rijksmonument|Dutch national heritage site]].\n\n== Early life ==\nVan Pallaes was born in 1587 in the Dutch city of [[Utrecht]]. She was the oldest child of Lubbert Jansz van Pallaes (died 1610) and Maria Johansdr van Reede (died 1649). She had two younger brothers: Lubbertus (died 1624) and Johan (died 1650). Both her parents came from [[Patrician (post-Roman Europe)|patrician families]] and she was raised as a [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]].{{sfn|Aanstoot|2015|p=5}}<ref name=\"1001 bio\">{{Cite encyclopedia |title=Pallaes, Maria van (1587-1664) |encyclopedia=1001 vrouwen uit de Nederlandse geschiedenis |publisher=Uitgeverij Vantilt |url=http://resources.huygens.knaw.nl/vrouwenlexicon/lemmata/data/pallaes |accessdate=6 July 2019 |last=Volbeda |first=Marja |date=13 February 2013 |editor-last=Hell |editor-first=Maarten |publication-place=Nijmegen, Netherlands |at=Biography nr. 205 |language=nl-NL |isbn=9789460041419 |editor-last2=Huiskamp |editor-first2=Marloes |via=Digitaal Vrouwenlexicon van Nederland}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 January 1606, at the age of 19, Van Pallaes married Hendrick van Schroyesteijn, a lawyer at the court of Utrecht, in the presence of the city's [[schepen|aldermen]]. He was also a Roman Catholic. Van Pallaes had more possessions and capital than Van Schroyesteijn at the time of their marriage. They bought a house along the [[Oudegracht]] but later moved to {{lang|nl|'t Groot Huijs}} on {{ill|Oudkerkhof|nl}} where Van Pallaes lived for the rest of her life.<ref name=FOOTNOTEAanstoot20155 /> The couple had six children: Johan, Lubbertus, Adriana, Margaretha, Livinius and Hendrick. In Van Pallaes and Van Schroyesteijn's [[Will and testament|will]] of 1624, their oldest son, Johan, was not mentioned as an heir; he was presumably disinherited but it is not known why. From 1624 Johan was not mentioned in any other documents or wills by Van Pallaes and Van Schroyesteijn.{{Sfn|Cornelis|1996|pp=153\u2013154}} The youngest child, Hendrick, had not yet been born in 1624 and is therefore not mentioned in the will.{{sfn|Aanstoot|2015|p=6}}\n\nVan Pallaes and Van Schroyesteijn remained Roman Catholics for the rest of their lives. As a result of the [[History of the Netherlands#The Reformation|Dutch Reformation]], practising their Catholic faith had been prohibited in Utrecht since 1580. Nevertheless, they continued their devotions, making use of [[clandestine church]]es; Van Pallaes' mother similarly practised Catholicism in Utrecht after the Reformation, despite having been raised as a [[Calvinism|Calvinist]]. Two of Van Pallaes' children had Catholic [[religious vocation]]s: Hendrick became a [[priest]] and Adriana became a [[Carmelites|Carmelite]] in [[Antwerp]].{{sfn|Cornelis|1996|p=153}}\n\n== Later life ==\nVan Pallaes lost most of her loved ones in her later life. First, her son Livinius died when about 10 in 1624.{{sfn|Aanstoot|2015|pp=6\u20137}}{{sfn|Aanstoot|2015|p=2}} Six years later, her husband, Van Schroyesteijn, died in 1630. She also lost four other children: Margaretha, the only child to be married,<ref name=\"1001 bio\" /> died in 1645; Lubbertus in 1646, Hendrick before 1649, and Johan, the oldest child, in {{circa|1649}}.<ref name=FOOTNOTEAanstoot20152 /> As all Van Pallaes' children remained childless, there were no grandchildren.<ref name=\"1001 bio\" />{{sfn|Aanstoot|2015|p=7}}\n\nVan Pallaes owned various houses in Utrecht as well as [[estate (land)|estate]]s and residences in the surroundings. In 1649, she sent a request to the government of Utrecht, asking for permission to freely decide over her inheritance.<ref name=\"1001 bio\" /> Her only remaining child, Adriana, was a member of a [[Mendicant orders|mendicant order]] and, as such, was not able to inherit. If Van Pallaes had not filed a request, her family fortune would have gone to the community of Utrecht. She decided to use her funds as [[Charity (practice)|charity]] for the city's needy inhabitants. It is likely that she did not just do so because she cared for the poor but because she believed she would be rewarded with a place in [[heaven]] after her death.{{sfn|Cornelis|1996|p=154}}\n\n=== Foundation of the first almshouses ===\n[[File:Agnietenstraat hoek Nieuwe Gracht naar het noord-westen - Utrecht - 20234995 - RCE.jpg|thumb|right|The 12 almshouses founded by Van Pallaes. The corner house is the refectory.|alt=A black and white picture showing a row of houses, taken from the corner of the street]]\n\nIn 1651, Van Pallaes bought [[real estate|land]] from Utrecht's {{ill|Agnietenklooster (Utrecht)|lt=Agnietenmonastery|nl}} to establish a {{lang|nl|[[hofje]]}} or collection of buildings with an adjoining court on the street now known as the Agnietenstraat. She charged a [[general contractor]] (whose identity is not known) to build 12 almshouses and a [[refectory]] there.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTECornelis1996154\" /> Each house was designed to have two floors, with two rooms on each floor, except for one of them, which had a different layout. The houses were {{convert|4.5 x 7|m|ft}}, with a [[Community gardening|community garden]] to the rear. This garden had a few toilets attached to its walls in groups of two or three and connected to a [[cesspit]].{{sfn|Aanstoot|2015|pp=10\u201311}}\n\nThe corner house served as a refectory and meeting place for the administrators of the foundation (who were appointed to that position by Van Pallaes in her will). Residents could only eat in the refectory if, for some reason, they were unable to eat in their own homes. Sometimes they  were invited to the refectory to meet the administrators. The refectory was rebuilt as an additional building in 1667, three years after Van Pallaes' death. As of 2019, the building still maintains the original locks.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEAanstoot201510\u201311\" />\n\nAll residents of the houses were subject to various conditions. First of all, those receiving support from the [[Deacon|diaconate]] or similar sources were not eligible for residence. Second, residents were housed either with their spouse or with another individual of the same sex. If a spouse died, they were not allowed to [[Remarriage|remarry]] and were forced to leave. Third, residents who committed physical violence or had an \"unsuitable\" lifestyle were dismissed. Fourth, when residents died, their inheritance was transferred to the Maria van Pallaes Foundation, which paid for their [[funeral]]. Unusually for the times, Van Pallaes allowed both Catholics and [[Protestantism|Protestants]] to live in the houses.{{sfn|Aanstoot|2015|p=12}}\n\nEvery year, the residents received wheat, butter and cheese, partly grown by Van Pallaes' [[tenant farmer]]s, from the foundation. Van Pallaes was probably present herself on such occasions. After her death, the foundation's administrators handed out the food while sitting under a painting of Van Pallaes. In 1849, residents started receiving [[Dutch guilder|\u0192]]10, {{convert|70|kg|lb}} of [[potatoes]] and {{convert|100|L|impgal}} of [[coal]] every year instead of the wheat, butter and cheese.<ref name=\"1001 bio\" /> Towards the end of the 20th century, they stopped receiving money, as new [[social security]] programs rendered financial support unnecessary.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEAanstoot201512\" />\n\n== Death ==\nAfter a long period of sickness, Van Pallaes died on 23 October 1664. An extensive and costly funeral ceremony was held following her death. The bells of [[St. Martin's Cathedral, Utrecht|St. Martin's Cathedral]] were rung, as were those of St. Jan's Church, the [[Buurkerk]] and Saint Nicholas' Church.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEAanstoot20157\" /> After the funeral, she was interred in her family grave at St. Martin's Cathedral. Ten years later, the grave was destroyed in a [[tornado]].{{sfn|Cornelis|1996|p=157}}\n\n=== Inheritance ===\nAfter Van Palleas' death, her property was inherited by the Maria van Pallaes Foundation, which was headed by the two directors she had appointed. From that point on, incumbent directors would select their successors themselves. Over the course of the foundation's existence, an additional 28 almshouses were constructed using Van Pallaes' inheritance. The foundation continued to operate until 1910, when the [[college van burgemeester en wethouders|municipal executive board]] of Utrecht started managing the houses. In 1978, the municipality bought the houses, transferring ownership of the original 12 almshouses and the refectory to the [[Utrecht Monument Foundation]] two years later.<ref name=\"1001 bio\" />\n\n== Legacy ==\nThe foundation's original almshouses and refectory were granted ''[[rijksmonument]]'' status in 1967 which, as of March 2020, they still hold.<ref>{{Citation |title=36005 Agnietenstraat 8 3512 XB te Utrecht |url=https://monumentenregister.cultureelerfgoed.nl/monumenten/36005 |language=nl |access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, a [[corbel]] was revealed honouring Van Palles. The corbel shows two hands giving away apples and was designed and created by Cissy van der Wel.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nieuws030.nl/nieuws/console-ter-ere-van-weldoenster-maria-van-pallaes/ |title=Console ter ere van weldoenster Maria van Pallaes |date=22 April 2015 |work=Nieuws 030 |access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Painting by Hendrick Bloemaert ===\n[[File:Hendrick Bloemaert Uitdeling aan de armen door Maria van Pallaes 1657.jpg|thumb|centre|upright=2.5|''Yearly food distribution to the poor of Utrecht by Maria van Pallaes'', a painting by [[Hendrick Bloemaert]] (1657). The woman sitting on the right is Van Pallaes, with her children in the background, and the houses in the background on the righthand side are the Maria van Pallaes houses.|alt=A painting that shows a woman, Van Pallaes, sitting on a chair with various well-dressed individuals behind her. Other people on the painting show gratitude whilst receiving food.]]\n\nSince 1924, the 1657 painting ''Yearly food distribution to the poor of Utrecht by Maria van Pallaes'' by [[Hendrick Bloemaert]] has belonged to  the collection of the [[Centraal Museum]] and has been included in various exhibitions, most recently in Brazil's [[Pinacoteca do Estado de S\u00e3o Paulo]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.centraalmuseum.nl/nl/collectie/2569-de-jaarlijkse-voedseluitdeling-aan-de-armen-door-maria-van-pallaes-hendrick-bloemaert |title=De jaarlijkse voedseluitdeling aan de armen door Maria van Pallaes |website=Centraal Museum |language=nl |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Literature ===\n*{{Cite book |title=Fundatie Maria van Pallaes 350 jaar |last=Aanstoot |first=Bert |publisher=Utrechts Monumentenfonds |year=2015 |language=nl-NL |trans-title=Maria van Pallaes Foundation 350 years |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book |title=Utrechtse biografie\u00ebn |chapter=Maria van Pallaes (1587\u20131664) |last=Cornelis |first=M. |publisher=Boom/Broese Kemink/SPOU |year=1996 |isbn=9053521836 |editor-last=Aalbers |editor-first=J. |volume=3 |publication-place=Utrecht/Amsterdam |pages=153\u2013157 |language=nl-NL |trans-title=Utrecht biographies |editor-last2=Van den Broeke |editor-first2=W. |editor-last3=Buiter |editor-first3=H. |editor-last4=Van den Hoven van Genderen |editor-first4=A.J. |editor-last5=Pietersma |editor-first5=A. |editor-last6=Vogelzang |editor-first6=F. |ref=harv}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pallaes, Maria van}}\n[[Category:1587 births]]\n[[Category:1664 deaths]]\n[[Category:17th-century Dutch people]]\n[[Category:17th-century Dutch women]]\n[[Category:Dutch philanthropists]]\n[[Category:People from Utrecht]]\n[[Category:Women philanthropists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Dutch philanthropist}}\n{{Dutch name|Van Pallaes|Pallaes}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = \n| name               = Maria van Pallaes\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = Maria van Pallaes, by Anthony Grolman, after Hendrick Bloemaert.jpg\n| caption            = 1878 painting of Van Pallaes, based on [[Hendrick Bloemaert]]'s portrait\n| pronunciation      = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth year|1587}}\n| birth_place        = [[Utrecht]], the Netherlands\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|1664|10|23|1587|df=yes}}\n| death_place        = Utrecht\n| burial_place       = [[St. Martin's Cathedral, Utrecht|St. Martin's Cathedral]], Utrecht\n| burial_coordinates = {{coord|52|05|27|N|5|07|18|E|region:NL_type:landmark_source:nlwiki|display=inline}}\n| occupation         = \n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = [[Philanthropy]]\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Hendrick van Schroyesteijn|11 January 1606|1630|end=d}}\n| children           = 6\n}}\n\n'''Mayken Lubbert van Pallaesdr.'''{{refn|group=note|Bert Aanstoot refers to her full name with a [[full stop]] at the end,<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEAanstoot20155\" /> while M. Cornelis does not include a full stop.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTECornelis1996153\" />}} (1587 \u2013 23 October 1664), commonly known as '''Maria van Pallaes''',{{refn|group=note|{{IPA-nl|ma\u02d0ria\u02d0 van p\u0251l\u0251is}}}} was a Dutch [[Philanthropy|philanthropist]] who established the Maria van Pallaes houses in the city of [[Utrecht]]. They consist of 12 [[almshouse]]s and a [[refectory]], together with a {{lang|nl|[[hofje]]}} or courtyard garden, to be used by the city's [[Poverty|poor]]. After her death, the buildings were placed under the control of the Maria van Pallaes Foundation and another 28 almshouses were later built using her [[inheritance]]. The original 12 houses and refectory are now owned by the {{ill|Utrechts Monumentenfonds|lt=Utrecht Monument Foundation|nl||WD=}} and are a [[Rijksmonument|Dutch national heritage site]].\n\n== Early life ==\nVan Pallaes was born in 1587 in the Dutch city of [[Utrecht]]. She was the oldest child of Lubbert Jansz van Pallaes (died 1610) and Maria Johansdr van Reede (died 1649). She had two younger brothers: Lubbertus (died 1624) and Johan (died 1650). Both her parents came from [[Patrician (post-Roman Europe)|patrician families]] and she was raised as a [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]].{{sfn|Aanstoot|2015|p=5}}<ref name=\"1001 bio\">{{Cite encyclopedia |title=Pallaes, Maria van (1587-1664) |encyclopedia=1001 vrouwen uit de Nederlandse geschiedenis |publisher=Uitgeverij Vantilt |url=http://resources.huygens.knaw.nl/vrouwenlexicon/lemmata/data/pallaes |accessdate=6 July 2019 |last=Volbeda |first=Marja |date=13 February 2013 |editor-last=Hell |editor-first=Maarten |publication-place=Nijmegen, Netherlands |at=Biography nr. 205 |language=nl-NL |isbn=9789460041419 |editor-last2=Huiskamp |editor-first2=Marloes |via=Digitaal Vrouwenlexicon van Nederland}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 January 1606, at the age of 19, Van Pallaes married Hendrick van Schroyesteijn, a lawyer at the court of Utrecht, in the presence of the city's [[schepen|aldermen]]. He was also a Roman Catholic. Van Pallaes had more possessions and capital than Van Schroyesteijn at the time of their marriage. They bought a house along the [[Oudegracht]] but later moved to {{lang|nl|'t Groot Huijs}} on {{ill|Oudkerkhof|nl}} where Van Pallaes lived for the rest of her life.<ref name=FOOTNOTEAanstoot20155 /> The couple had six children: Johan, Lubbertus, Adriana, Margaretha, Livinius and Hendrick. In Van Pallaes and Van Schroyesteijn's [[Will and testament|will]] of 1624, their oldest son, Johan, was not mentioned as an heir; he was presumably disinherited but it is not known why. From 1624 Johan was not mentioned in any other documents or wills by Van Pallaes and Van Schroyesteijn.{{Sfn|Cornelis|1996|pp=153\u2013154}} The youngest child, Hendrick, had not yet been born in 1624 and is therefore not mentioned in the will.{{sfn|Aanstoot|2015|p=6}}\n\nVan Pallaes and Van Schroyesteijn remained Roman Catholics for the rest of their lives. As a result