mshouses ===\n[[File:Agnietenstraat hoek Nieuwe Gracht naar het noord-westen - Utrecht - 20234995 - RCE.jpg|thumb|right|The 12 almshouses founded by Van Pallaes. The corner house is the refectory.|alt=A black and white picture showing a row of houses, taken from the corner of the street]]\n\nIn 1651, Van Pallaes bought [[real estate|land]] from Utrecht's {{ill|Agnietenklooster (Utrecht)|lt=Agnietenmonastery|nl}} to establish a {{lang|nl|[[hofje]]}} or collection of buildings with an adjoining court on the street now known as the Agnietenstraat. She charged a [[general contractor]] (whose identity is not known) to build 12 almshouses and a [[refectory]] there.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTECornelis1996154\" /> Each house was designed to have two floors, with two rooms on each floor, except for one of them, which had a different layout. The houses were {{convert|4.5 x 7|m|ft}}, with a [[Community gardening|community garden]] to the rear. This garden had a few toilets attached to its walls in groups of two or three and connected to a [[cesspit]].{{sfn|Aanstoot|2015|pp=10\u201311}}\n\nThe corner house served as a refectory and meeting place for the administrators of the foundation (who were appointed to that position by Van Pallaes in her will). Residents could only eat in the refectory if, for some reason, they were unable to eat in their own homes. Sometimes they  were invited to the refectory to meet the administrators. The refectory was rebuilt as an additional building in 1667, three years after Van Pallaes' death. As of 2019, the building still maintains the original locks.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEAanstoot201510\u201311\" />\n\nAll residents of the houses were subject to various conditions. First of all, those receiving support from the [[Deacon|diaconate]] or similar sources were not eligible for residence. Second, residents were housed either with their spouse or with another individual of the same sex. If a spouse died, they were not allowed to [[Remarriage|remarry]] and were forced to leave. Third, residents who committed physical violence or had an \"unsuitable\" lifestyle were dismissed. Fourth, when residents died, their inheritance was transferred to the Maria van Pallaes Foundation, which paid for their [[funeral]]. Unusually for the times, Van Pallaes allowed both Catholics and [[Protestantism|Protestants]] to live in the houses.{{sfn|Aanstoot|2015|p=12}}\n\nEvery year, the residents received wheat, butter and cheese, partly grown by Van Pallaes' [[tenant farmer]]s, from the foundation. Van Pallaes was probably present herself on such occasions. After her death, the foundation's administrators handed out the food while sitting under a painting of Van Pallaes. In 1849, residents started receiving [[Dutch guilder|\u0192]]10, {{convert|70|kg|lb}} of [[potatoes]] and {{convert|100|L|impgal}} of [[coal]] every year instead of the wheat, butter and cheese.<ref name=\"1001 bio\" /> Towards the end of the 20th century, they stopped receiving money, as new [[social security]] programs rendered financial support unnecessary.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEAanstoot201512\" />\n\n== Death ==\nAfter a long period of sickness, Van Pallaes died on 23 October 1664. An extensive and costly funeral ceremony was held following her death. The bells of [[St. Martin's Cathedral, Utrecht|St. Martin's Cathedral]] were rung, as were those of St. Jan's Church, the [[Buurkerk]] and Saint Nicholas' Church.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEAanstoot20157\" /> After the funeral, she was interred in her family grave at St. Martin's Cathedral. Ten years later, the grave was destroyed in a [[tornado]].{{sfn|Cornelis|1996|p=157}}\n\n=== Inheritance ===\nAfter Van Palleas' death, her property was inherited by the Maria van Pallaes Foundation, which was headed by the two directors she had appointed. From that point on, incumbent directors would select their successors themselves. Over the course of the foundation's existence, an additional 28 almshouses were constructed using Van Pallaes' inheritance. The foundation continued to operate until 1910, when the [[college van burgemeester en wethouders|municipal executive board]] of Utrecht started managing the houses. In 1978, the municipality bought the houses, transferring ownership of the original 12 almshouses and the refectory to the [[Utrecht Monument Foundation]] two years later.<ref name=\"1001 bio\" />\n\n== Legacy ==\nThe foundation's original almshouses and refectory were granted ''[[rijksmonument]]'' status in 1967 which, as of March 2020, they still hold.<ref>{{Citation |title=36005 Agnietenstraat 8 3512 XB te Utrecht |url=https://monumentenregister.cultureelerfgoed.nl/monumenten/36005 |language=nl |access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, a [[corbel]] was revealed honouring Van Palles. The corbel shows two hands giving away apples and was designed and created by Cissy van der Wel.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nieuws030.nl/nieuws/console-ter-ere-van-weldoenster-maria-van-pallaes/ |title=Console ter ere van weldoenster Maria van Pallaes |date=22 April 2015 |work=Nieuws 030 |access-date=22 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Painting by Hendrick Bloemaert ===\n[[File:Hendrick Bloemaert Uitdeling aan de armen door Maria van Pallaes 1657.jpg|thumb|centre|upright=2.5|''Yearly food distribution to the poor of Utrecht by Maria van Pallaes'', a painting by [[Hendrick Bloemaert]] (1657). The woman sitting on the right is Van Pallaes, with her children in the background, and the houses in the background on the righthand side are the Maria van Pallaes houses.|alt=A painting that shows a woman, Van Pallaes, sitting on a chair with various well-dressed individuals behind her. Other people on the painting show gratitude whilst receiving food.]]\n\nSince 1924, the 1657 painting ''Yearly food distribution to the poor of Utrecht by Maria van Pallaes'' by [[Hendrick Bloemaert]] has belonged to  the collection of the [[Centraal Museum]] and has been included in various exhibitions, most recently in Brazil's [[Pinacoteca do Estado de S\u00e3o Paulo]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.centraalmuseum.nl/nl/collectie/2569-de-jaarlijkse-voedseluitdeling-aan-de-armen-door-maria-van-pallaes-hendrick-bloemaert |title=De jaarlijkse voedseluitdeling aan de armen door Maria van Pallaes |website=Centraal Museum |language=nl |access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Literature ===\n*{{Cite book |title=Fundatie Maria van Pallaes 350 jaar |last=Aanstoot |first=Bert |publisher=Utrechts Monumentenfonds |year=2015 |language=nl-NL |trans-title=Maria van Pallaes Foundation 350 years |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book |title=Utrechtse biografie\u00ebn |chapter=Maria van Pallaes (1587\u20131664) |last=Cornelis |first=M. |publisher=Boom/Broese Kemink/SPOU |year=1996 |isbn=9053521836 |editor-last=Aalbers |editor-first=J. |volume=3 |publication-place=Utrecht/Amsterdam |pages=153\u2013157 |language=nl-NL |trans-title=Utrecht biographies |editor-last2=Van den Broeke |editor-first2=W. |editor-last3=Buiter |editor-first3=H. |editor-last4=Van den Hoven van Genderen |editor-first4=A.J. |editor-last5=Pietersma |editor-first5=A. |editor-last6=Vogelzang |editor-first6=F. |ref=harv}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pallaes, Maria van}}\n[[Category:1587 births]]\n[[Category:1664 deaths]]\n[[Category:17th-century Dutch people]]\n[[Category:17th-century Dutch women]]\n[[Category:Dutch philanthropists]]\n[[Category:People from Utrecht]]\n[[Category:Women philanthropists]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maria_van_Pallaes"}
{"title_page": "Clara Harris", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|American socialite}}\n{{about|the American socialite|the murder suspect known as Clara Harris|murder of David Lynn Harris}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image                     = Miss Clara Harris (Married Major Rathbone) (4190098611) copy.jpg\n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = Harris photographed by [[Mathew Brady]] (ca. 1860\u20131865)\n| birth_name                = Clara Hamilton Harris\n| birth_date                = {{birth date|1834|9|4|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place               = [[Albany, New York|Albany]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| death_date                = {{death date and age|1883|12|23|1834|9|4|mf=yes}}\n| death_place               = [[Hildesheim]], [[Lower Saxony]], [[German Empire]]\n| death_cause               = [[Gunshot wound]] to the head\n| resting_place             = Stadtfriedhof Engesohde (disinterred in 1952)\n| nationality               = American\n| known_for                 = \n| spouse                    = {{marriage|[[Henry Rathbone]]|1867|1883}}\n| children                  = [[Henry Riggs Rathbone]]<br />Gerald Lawrence Rathbone<br />Clara Pauline Rathbone\n| parents                   = [[Ira Harris]]<br />Louisa Tubbs Harris\n}}\n'''Clara Hamilton Harris''' (September 4, 1834<ref name=\"thomas\">{{cite book|last=Ham|first=Mrs. Thomas H. |title=A Genealogy Of the Descendants Of Nicholas Harris, M.D.,|url=https://archive.org/details/genealogyofdesce00hamt|year=1904|publisher=C.I.F. Ham|page=[https://archive.org/details/genealogyofdesce00hamt/page/18 18]}}</ref>&nbsp;\u2013 December 23, 1883) was an American socialite. Harris and her fianc\u00e9, [[Henry Rathbone|Major Henry Rathbone]], were the guests of [[Abraham Lincoln|President Lincoln]] and [[Mary Todd Lincoln|First Lady Mary Lincoln]] when [[John Wilkes Booth]] fatally [[Assassination of Abraham Lincoln|shot the President]] at [[Ford's Theatre]] in April 1865.\n\n==Family==\nHarris was born in [[Albany, New York]],<ref name=\"thomas1\">Thomas 1904 p.27</ref> one of four children of [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] [[Ira Harris]] of [[New York (state)|New York]], and his first wife Louisa Harris (n\u00e9e Tubbs).<ref>{{cite book|last=Seward|first=Frances Adeline |editor=Johnson, Patricia Carley |title=Sensitivity and Civil War, the Selected Diaries and Papers, 1858\u20131866, of Frances Adeline (Fanny) Seward|volume=2|year=1963|publisher=University of Rochester|page=719}}</ref> Harris' mother Louisa died in 1845. On August 1, 1848, Ira Harris married Pauline Rathbone (n\u00e9e Penney),<ref name=\"thomas\" /> the widow of Jared L. Rathbone, a successful merchant who later became the mayor of Albany.<ref>{{cite book|title=Essex Institute Historical Collections|year=1891|publisher=Essex Institute Press|page=165}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Updike|first=John|title=More Matter: Essays and Criticism|year=2009|publisher=Random House Digital, Inc.|isbn=0-307-48839-X|page=301}}</ref> Jared and Pauline Rathbone had four children (two of whom, Anna and Charles, died in infancy) including sons, Jared, Jr. and [[Henry Rathbone]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Talcott|first=Sebastian V.|title=Genealogical Notes of New York and New England Families|year=2001|publisher=Heritage Books|isbn=0-788-41956-0|page=634}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Harris and Henry Rathbone were raised in the same household and were related by their parents' marriage, they fell in love and later became engaged.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-08-21/entertainment/9408210103_1_henry-and-clara-henry-rathbone-thomas-mallon|title=Henry And Clara's Cruel Fate|last=Pappas|first=Theodore|date=August 21, 1994|publisher=chicagotribune.com|page=1|accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref> Their engagement was interrupted when the [[American Civil War]] broke out in 1861 and Henry Rathbone joined the [[Union Army]] that year and became major in 1869 upon joining the 5th United States Infantry<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k_Co6TgBGQUC&pg=PA161&lpg=PA161&dq=clara+hamilton+harris&source=bl&ots=RJQhZzkmc7&sig=ACfU3U1MeNMS7UVlxduXP_VWNW5fKvZ_Nw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjEruCs0tXhAhXjUt8KHexvC-A4ChDoATAFegQIBhAB#v=onepage&q=clara%20hamilton%20harris&f=false|title=Protecting President Lincoln: The Security Effort, the Thwarted Plots and the Disaster at Ford's Theatre|last=Hatch|first=Frederick|date=October 14, 2011|publisher=McFarland|isbn=9780786486915|language=en}}</ref>.<ref>{{cite book|editor=Steers, Edward |title=The Trial: The Assassination of President Lincoln and the Trial of the Conspirators|year=2010|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|isbn=0-813-12724-6|page=XLII}}</ref>  \n\n==Lincoln assassination==\n{{Main|Assassination of Abraham Lincoln}}\n[[File:Lincoln assassination slide c1900 - Restoration.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Image of Lincoln being shot by Booth while sitting in a theater booth.|Shown in the presidential booth of Ford's Theatre, from left to right, are assassin [[John Wilkes Booth]], [[Abraham Lincoln]], [[Mary Todd Lincoln]], Clara Harris, and [[Henry Rathbone]]]]\n\nOn April 14, 1865, Major Rathbone and his fianc\u00e9e Clara accepted an invitation to see a play at [[Ford's Theatre]] from President [[Abraham Lincoln]] and his wife, First Lady [[Mary Todd Lincoln]]. The couple, who had been friends with the President and his wife for some time, were invited after [[Ulysses S. Grant]] and his wife [[Julia Grant|Julia]], [[Thomas Eckert]] and several other people had declined Mrs. Lincoln's invitation to the play.<ref>{{cite book|last=Steers|first=Edward |title=Blood on the Moon: The Assassination of Abraham Lincoln|year=2005|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|isbn=0-813-19151-3|pages=104\u2013105}}</ref>\n\nWhile watching the play ''[[Our American Cousin]]'' in the Presidential Box at Ford's Theatre that evening, [[John Wilkes Booth]] fatally shot President Lincoln in the back of the head. When Rathbone attempted to apprehend Booth after the shooting, Booth slashed Rathbone with a [[Bowie knife]] from left elbow to shoulder.<ref name=lachman>{{cite book|last=Lachman|first=Charles|title=The Last Lincolns: The Rise & Fall of a Great American Family|year=2008|publisher=Sterling Publishing Company|isbn=1-402-75890-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/lastlincolnsrise0000lach/page/288 288]|url=https://archive.org/details/lastlincolnsrise0000lach/page/288}}</ref><ref name=\"hatch\">{{cite book|last=Hatch|first=Frederick |title=Protecting President Lincoln: The Security Effort, the Thwarted Plots, and the Disaster at Ford's Theatre|year=2011|publisher=McFarland|isbn=0-786-46362-7|page=161}}</ref>  Rathbone lost a considerable amount of blood which stained Harris' white dress, face and hands when she attempted to aid him.<ref name=Smith1>{{cite journal|last=Smith|first=Gene|date=February\u2013March 1994|title=The Haunted Major|journal=American Heritage|volume=45|issue=1|page=1|url=http://www.americanheritage.com/content/haunted-major}}</ref>\n\nDespite being seriously wounded, Rathbone escorted First Lady Mary Lincoln to the Petersen House where doctors had decided to take the mortally wounded President. Shortly after arriving at the Petersen House, Rathbone passed out due to loss of blood.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bain|first=Robert T.|title=Lincoln's Last Battleground: A Tragic Night Recalled|year=2005|publisher=AuthorHouse|isbn=1-467-02991-2|page=19}}</ref> Harris arrived at the house soon after and held Rathbone's head in her lap while he drifted in and out of consciousness. A surgeon who had been attending the President finally examined Rathbone and realized his wound was more serious than initially thought. Booth had severed an artery located just above Rathbone's elbow and had cut him nearly to the bone. Rathbone was taken home while Harris decided to stay with Mrs. Lincoln.<ref name=kauffman>Kauffman (2007) p.37</ref> Harris later stated:\n\n<blockquote>Poor Mrs. Lincoln, all through that dreadful night would look at me with horror & scream, 'oh! my husband's blood, my dear husband's blood'...It was Henry's blood, not the president's, but explanations were pointless.<ref name=kauffman/></blockquote>\n\nWhile Rathbone eventually recovered from the attack, President Lincoln died of his wound the following morning. After the assassination, Rathbone blamed himself for not preventing Lincoln's death. He spent the remainder of his life battling delusions and seeking treatments for other physical problems including constant headaches.<ref name=lachman /><ref name=\"hatch\" />\n\n==Later years and death==\nHarris and Rathbone were married on July 11, 1867. The couple had three children: [[Henry Riggs Rathbone|Henry Riggs]] (born February 12, 1870), who later became a [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Congressman]] from [[Illinois]], Gerald Lawrence (born August 26, 1871) and Clara Pauline (born September 15, 1872).<ref name=\"thomas1\" /><ref>Talcott 2001 p.637</ref>  Rathbone, who had risen to the rank of [[colonel]], resigned from the Army in December 1870.<ref>{{cite book|last=Jampoler|first=Andrew C. A.|title=The Last Lincoln Conspirator: John Surratt's Flight from the Gallows|year=2008|publisher=Naval Institute Press|isbn=1-591-14407-8|page=[https://archive.org/details/lastlincolnconsp0000jamp/page/182 182]|url=https://archive.org/details/lastlincolnconsp0000jamp/page/182}}</ref> The family settled in Washington D.C. where Rathbone's mental health deteriorated.<ref name=\"hatch\" />  Rathbone's behavior became increasingly erratic and he began drinking heavily, gambling and having affairs. Due to his behavior, Rathbone found it difficult to hold a job for an extended period of time.<ref name=papas2>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-08-21/entertainment/9408210103_1_henry-and-clara-henry-rathbone-thomas-mallon/2|title=Henry And Clara's Cruel Fate|last=Pappas|first=Theodore|date=August 21, 1994|publisher=chicagotribune.com|page=2|accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nEvery year on the anniversary of Lincoln's assassination, journalists would contact the couple with questions about Lincoln's death, furthering Rathbone's feelings of guilt. Harris later wrote to a friend:\n\n<blockquote>I understand his distress...in every hotel we're in, as soon as people get wind of our presence, we feel ourselves become objects of morbid scrutiny.... Whenever we were in the dining room, we began to feel like zoo animals. Henry...imagines that the whispering is more pointed and malicious than it can possibly be.<ref name=papas2/></blockquote>\n\nAs time went on, Rathbone's mental instability worsened and he often became jealous of other men who paid attention to Harris and resented the attention Harris paid their children. He also reportedly threatened his wife on several occasions, convinced that Harris was going to divorce him and take the children.<ref name=\"hatch\" /><ref name=Smith1 /> Despite his behavior, Rathbone was appointed [[Consul (representative)|U.S. Consul]] to the [[Province of Hanover]] by President [[Chester Alan Arthur]] in 1882. The family relocated to Germany where Rathbone's mental health continued to decline.<ref>{{cite book|last=Steers|first=Edward |title=The Lincoln Assassination Encyclopedia|year=2010|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=0-061-98705-0|page=158}}</ref>\n\nOn December 23, 1883, Henry Rathbone attacked his family in a fit of madness. He fatally shot his wife in the head and then attempted to kill the children, but a groundskeeper prevented him from doing so. Rathbone then stabbed himself five times in the chest in an attempted suicide.<ref>{{cite book|last=Swanson|first=James L. |title=Manhunt: The 12-Day Chase to Catch Lincoln's Killer|year=2009|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=0-061-80397-9|page=372}}</ref> Blaming his crime on an intruder, Rathbone was charged with murder and declared insane by doctors. He was convicted and committed to an asylum for the criminally insane in [[Hildesheim]], [[Germany]], where he died on August 14, 1911. The couple's children were sent to live with their uncle, William Harris, in the United States.<ref name=\"hatch\" />\n\nHarris was buried in the city cemetery at [[Hanover]]/Engesohde. Her husband was buried next to her upon his death in 1911. In 1952, the \nRathbones' remains were disinterred and disposed of after cemetery management determined that their graves had not been visited or were no longer of interest to the family.<ref name=smith2>{{cite journal|last=Smith|first=Gene|date=February\u2013March 1994|title=The Haunted Major|journal=American Heritage|volume=45|issue=1|page=2|url=http://www.americanheritage.com/content/haunted-major?page=2}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n* Clara Harris kept the bloodied white dress she wore on the night of assassination. Unable to bring herself to wash or destroy it, she eventually stored it in a closet in the family's summer home near Albany. After experiencing what she claimed was a visit from [[Lincoln's ghost]], Harris had the closet in which the dress was stored covered with bricks. In 1910, Henry Riggs Rathbone, Harris and Rathbone's eldest son, removed the bricks and had the dress destroyed reportedly claiming that it had cursed the family.<ref name=Smith1 /> The dress was later the subject of the 1929 book ''The White Satin Dress'', by [[Mary Raymond Shipman Andrews]].<ref name=smith2 />\n* In 1994, [[Thomas Mallon]] released the novel ''Henry and Clara'', a fictional account of the lives of Harris and her husband.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,303433,00.html|title=Thomas Mallon|last=De Haven|first=Tom|date=August 19, 1994|publisher=ew.com|accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref>\n* Harris was portrayed by actress Mercedes Herrero in the made-for-television film ''[[The Day Lincoln Was Shot]]'' and by uncredited actresses in two films pertaining to the Lincoln assassination, ''[[The Conspirator]]'' and ''[[National Treasure: Book of Secrets]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n* {{Find a Grave|13980435}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harris, Clara}}\n[[Category:1834 births]]\n[[Category:1883 crimes]]\n[[Category:1883 deaths]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Germany]]\n[[Category:American people murdered abroad]]\n[[Category:American socialites]]\n[[Category:Burials in Lower Saxony]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Germany]]\n[[Category:People associated with the assassination of Abraham Lincoln]]\n[[Category:People from Albany, New York]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Germany]]\n[[Category:Women in the American Civil War]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American socialite}}\n{{about|the American socialite|the murder suspect known as Clara Harris|murder of David Lynn Harris}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image                     = Miss Clara Harris (Married Major Rathbone) (4190098611) copy.jpg\n| image_size                = \n| alt                       = \n| caption                   = Harris photographed by [[Mathew Brady]] (ca. 1860\u20131865)\n| birth_name                = Clara Hamilton Harris\n| birth_date                = {{birth date|1834|9|4|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place               = [[Albany, New York|Albany]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| death_date                = {{death date and age|1883|12|23|1834|9|4|mf=yes}}\n| death_place               = [[Hildesheim]], [[Lower Saxony]], [[German Empire]]\n| death_cause               = [[Gunshot wound]] to the head\n| resting_place             = Stadtfriedhof Engesohde (disinterred in 1952)\n| nationality               = American\n| known_for                 = \n| spouse                    = {{marriage|[[Henry Rathbone]]|1867|1883}}\n| children                  = [[Henry Riggs Rathbone]]<br />Gerald Lawrence Rathbone<br />Clara Pauline Rathbone\n| parents                   = [[Ira Harris]]<br />Louisa Tubbs Harris\n}}\n'''Clara Hamilton Harris''' (September 4, 1834<ref name=\"thomas\">{{cite book|last=Ham|first=Mrs. Thomas H. |title=A Genealogy Of the Descendants Of Nicholas Harris, M.D.,|url=https://archive.org/details/genealogyofdesce00hamt|year=1904|publisher=C.I.F. Ham|page=[https://archive.org/details/genealogyofdesce00hamt/page/18 18]}}</ref>&nbsp;\u2013 December 23, 1883) was an American socialite. Harris and her fianc\u00e9, [[Henry Rathbone|Major Henry Rathbone]], were the guests of [[Abraham Lincoln|President Lincoln]] and [[Mary Todd Lincoln|First Lady Mary Lincoln]] when [[John Wilkes Booth]] fatally [[Assassination of Abraham Lincoln|shot the President]] at [[Ford's Theatre]] in April 1865.\n\n==Family==\nHarris was born in [[Albany, New York]],<ref name=\"thomas1\">Thomas 1904 p.27</ref> one of four children of [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] [[Ira Harris]] of [[New York (state)|New York]], and his first wife Louisa Harris (n\u00e9e Tubbs).<ref>{{cite book|last=Seward|first=Frances Adeline |editor=Johnson, Patricia Carley |title=Sensitivity and Civil War, the Selected Diaries and Papers, 1858\u20131866, of Frances Adeline (Fanny) Seward|volume=2|year=1963|publisher=University of Rochester|page=719}}</ref> Harris' mother Louisa died in 1845. On August 1, 1848, Ira Harris married Pauline Rathbone (n\u00e9e Penney),<ref name=\"thomas\" /> the widow of Jared L. Rathbone, a successful merchant who later became the mayor of Albany.<ref>{{cite book|title=Essex Institute Historical Collections|year=1891|publisher=Essex Institute Press|page=165}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Updike|first=John|title=More Matter: Essays and Criticism|year=2009|publisher=Random House Digital, Inc.|isbn=0-307-48839-X|page=301}}</ref> Jared and Pauline Rathbone had four children (two of whom, Anna and Charles, died in infancy) including sons, Jared, Jr. and [[Henry Rathbone]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Talcott|first=Sebastian V.|title=Genealogical Notes of New York and New England Families|year=2001|publisher=Heritage Books|isbn=0-788-41956-0|page=634}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Harris and Henry Rathbone were raised in the same household and were related by their parents' marriage, they fell in love and later became engaged.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-08-21/entertainment/9408210103_1_henry-and-clara-henry-rathbone-thomas-mallon|title=Henry And Clara's Cruel Fate|last=Pappas|first=Theodore|date=August 21, 1994|publisher=chicagotribune.com|page=1|accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref> Their engagement was interrupted when the [[American Civil War]] broke out in 1861 and Henry Rathbone joined the [[Union Army]] that year and became major in 1869 upon joining the 5th United States Infantry<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k_Co6TgBGQUC&pg=PA161&lpg=PA161&dq=clara+hamilton+harris&source=bl&ots=RJQhZzkmc7&sig=ACfU3U1MeNMS7UVlxduXP_VWNW5fKvZ_Nw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjEruCs0tXhAhXjUt8KHexvC-A4ChDoATAFegQIBhAB#v=onepage&q=clara%20hamilton%20harris&f=false|title=Protecting President Lincoln: The Security Effort, the Thwarted Plots and the Disaster at Ford's Theatre|last=Hatch|first=Frederick|date=2011-10-14|publisher=McFarland|isbn=9780786486915|language=en}}</ref>.<ref>{{cite book|editor=Steers, Edward |title=The Trial: The Assassination of President Lincoln and the Trial of the Conspirators|year=2010|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|isbn=0-813-12724-6|page=XLII}}</ref>  \n\n==Lincoln assassination==\n{{Main|Assassination of Abraham Lincoln}}\n[[File:Lincoln assassination slide c1900 - Restoration.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Image of Lincoln being shot by Booth while sitting in a theater booth.|Shown in the presidential booth of Ford's Theatre, from left to right, are assassin [[John Wilkes Booth]], [[Abraham Lincoln]], [[Mary Todd Lincoln]], Clara Harris, and [[Henry Rathbone]]]]\n\nOn April 14, 1865, Major Rathbone and his fianc\u00e9e Clara accepted an invitation to see a play at [[Ford's Theatre]] from President [[Abraham Lincoln]] and his wife, First Lady [[Mary Todd Lincoln]]. The couple, who had been friends with the President and his wife for some time, were invited after [[Ulysses S. Grant]] and his wife [[Julia Grant|Julia]], [[Thomas Eckert]] and several other people had declined Mrs. Lincoln's invitation to the play.<ref>{{cite book|last=Steers|first=Edward |title=Blood on the Moon: The Assassination of Abraham Lincoln|year=2005|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|isbn=0-813-19151-3|pages=104\u2013105}}</ref>\n\nWhile watching the play ''[[Our American Cousin]]'' in the Presidential Box at Ford's Theatre that evening, [[John Wilkes Booth]] fatally shot President Lincoln in the back of the head. When Rathbone attempted to apprehend Booth after the shooting, Booth slashed Rathbone with a [[Bowie knife]] from left elbow to shoulder.<ref name=lachman>{{cite book|last=Lachman|first=Charles|title=The Last Lincolns: The Rise & Fall of a Great American Family|year=2008|publisher=Sterling Publishing Company|isbn=1-402-75890-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/lastlincolnsrise0000lach/page/288 288]|url=https://archive.org/details/lastlincolnsrise0000lach/page/288}}</ref><ref name=\"hatch\">{{cite book|last=Hatch|first=Frederick |title=Protecting President Lincoln: The Security Effort, the Thwarted Plots, and the Disaster at Ford's Theatre|year=2011|publisher=McFarland|isbn=0-786-46362-7|page=161}}</ref>  Rathbone lost a considerable amount of blood which stained Harris' white dress, face and hands when she attempted to aid him.<ref name=Smith1>{{cite journal|last=Smith|first=Gene|date=February\u2013March 1994|title=The Haunted Major|journal=American Heritage|volume=45|issue=1|page=1|url=http://www.americanheritage.com/content/haunted-major}}</ref>\n\nDespite being seriously wounded, Rathbone escorted First Lady Mary Lincoln to the Petersen House where doctors had decided to take the mortally wounded President. Shortly after arriving at the Petersen House, Rathbone passed out due to loss of blood.<ref>{{cite book|last=Bain|first=Robert T.|title=Lincoln's Last Battleground: A Tragic Night Recalled|year=2005|publisher=AuthorHouse|isbn=1-467-02991-2|page=19}}</ref> Harris arrived at the house soon after and held Rathbone's head in her lap while he drifted in and out of consciousness. A surgeon who had been attending the President finally examined Rathbone and realized his wound was more serious than initially thought. Booth had severed an artery located just above Rathbone's elbow and had cut him nearly to the bone. Rathbone was taken home while Harris decided to stay with Mrs. Lincoln.<ref name=kauffman>Kauffman (2007) p.37</ref> Harris later stated:\n\n<blockquote>Poor Mrs. Lincoln, all through that dreadful night would look at me with horror & scream, 'oh! my husband's blood, my dear husband's blood'...It was Henry's blood, not the president's, but explanations were pointless.<ref name=kauffman/></blockquote>\n\nWhile Rathbone eventually recovered from the attack, President Lincoln died of his wound the following morning. After the assassination, Rathbone blamed himself for not preventing Lincoln's death. He spent the remainder of his life battling delusions and seeking treatments for other physical problems including constant headaches.<ref name=lachman /><ref name=\"hatch\" />\n\n==Later years and death==\nHarris and Rathbone were married on July 11, 1867. The couple had three children: [[Henry Riggs Rathbone|Henry Riggs]] (born February 12, 1870), who later became a [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Congressman]] from [[Illinois]], Gerald Lawrence (born August 26, 1871) and Clara Pauline (born September 15, 1872).<ref name=\"thomas1\" /><ref>Talcott 2001 p.637</ref>  Rathbone, who had risen to the rank of [[colonel]], resigned from the Army in December 1870.<ref>{{cite book|last=Jampoler|first=Andrew C. A.|title=The Last Lincoln Conspirator: John Surratt's Flight from the Gallows|year=2008|publisher=Naval Institute Press|isbn=1-591-14407-8|page=[https://archive.org/details/lastlincolnconsp0000jamp/page/182 182]|url=https://archive.org/details/lastlincolnconsp0000jamp/page/182}}</ref> The family settled in Washington D.C. where Rathbone's mental health deteriorated.<ref name=\"hatch\" />  Rathbone's behavior became increasingly erratic and he began drinking heavily, gambling and having affairs. Due to his behavior, Rathbone found it difficult to hold a job for an extended period of time.<ref name=papas2>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1994-08-21/entertainment/9408210103_1_henry-and-clara-henry-rathbone-thomas-mallon/2|title=Henry And Clara's Cruel Fate|last=Pappas|first=Theodore|date=August 21, 1994|publisher=chicagotribune.com|page=2|accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nEvery year on the anniversary of Lincoln's assassination, journalists would contact the couple with questions about Lincoln's death, furthering Rathbone's feelings of guilt. Harris later wrote to a friend:\n\n<blockquote>I understand his distress...in every hotel we're in, as soon as people get wind of our presence, we feel ourselves become objects of morbid scrutiny.... Whenever we were in the dining room, we began to feel like zoo animals. Henry...imagines that the whispering is more pointed and malicious than it can possibly be.<ref name=papas2/></blockquote>\n\nAs time went on, Rathbone's mental instability worsened and he often became jealous of other men who paid attention to Harris and resented the attention Harris paid their children. He also reportedly threatened his wife on several occasions, convinced that Harris was going to divorce him and take the children.<ref name=\"hatch\" /><ref name=Smith1 /> Despite his behavior, Rathbone was appointed [[Consul (representative)|U.S. Consul]] to the [[Province of Hanover]] by President [[Chester Alan Arthur]] in 1882. The family relocated to Germany where Rathbone's mental health continued to decline.<ref>{{cite book|last=Steers|first=Edward |title=The Lincoln Assassination Encyclopedia|year=2010|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=0-061-98705-0|page=158}}</ref>\n\nOn December 23, 1883, Henry Rathbone attacked his family in a fit of madness. He fatally shot his wife in the head and then attempted to kill the children, but a groundskeeper prevented him from doing so. Rathbone then stabbed himself five times in the chest in an attempted suicide.<ref>{{cite book|last=Swanson|first=James L. |title=Manhunt: The 12-Day Chase to Catch Lincoln's Killer|year=2009|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=0-061-80397-9|page=372}}</ref> Blaming his crime on an intruder, Rathbone was charged with murder and declared insane by doctors. He was convicted and committed to an asylum for the criminally insane in [[Hildesheim]], [[Germany]], where he died on August 14, 1911. The couple's children were sent to live with their uncle, William Harris, in the United States.<ref name=\"hatch\" />\n\nHarris was buried in the city cemetery at [[Hanover]]/Engesohde. Her husband was buried next to her upon his death in 1911. In 1952, the \nRathbones' remains were disinterred and disposed of after cemetery management determined that their graves had not been visited or were no longer of interest to the family.<ref name=smith2>{{cite journal|last=Smith|first=Gene|date=February\u2013March 1994|title=The Haunted Major|journal=American Heritage|volume=45|issue=1|page=2|url=http://www.americanheritage.com/content/haunted-major?page=2}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n* Clara Harris kept the bloodied white dress she wore on the night of assassination. Unable to bring herself to wash or destroy it, she eventually stored it in a closet in the family's summer home near Albany. After experiencing what she claimed was a visit from [[Lincoln's ghost]], Harris had the closet in which the dress was stored covered with bricks. In 1910, Henry Riggs Rathbone, Harris and Rathbone's eldest son, removed the bricks and had the dress destroyed reportedly claiming that it had cursed the family.<ref name=Smith1 /> The dress was later the subject of the 1929 book ''The White Satin Dress'', by [[Mary Raymond Shipman Andrews]].<ref name=smith2 />\n* In 1994, [[Thomas Mallon]] released the novel ''Henry and Clara'', a fictional account of the lives of Harris and her husband.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,303433,00.html|title=Thomas Mallon|last=De Haven|first=Tom|date=August 19, 1994|publisher=ew.com|accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref>\n* Harris was portrayed by actress Mercedes Herrero in the made-for-television film ''[[The Day Lincoln Was Shot]]'' and by uncredited actresses in two films pertaining to the Lincoln assassination, ''[[The Conspirator]]'' and ''[[National Treasure: Book of Secrets]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography|American Civil War}}\n* {{Find a Grave|13980435}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Harris, Clara}}\n[[Category:1834 births]]\n[[Category:1883 crimes]]\n[[Category:1883 deaths]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Germany]]\n[[Category:American people murdered abroad]]\n[[Category:American socialites]]\n[[Category:Burials in Lower Saxony]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Germany]]\n[[Category:People associated with the assassination of Abraham Lincoln]]\n[[Category:People from Albany, New York]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Germany]]\n[[Category:Women in the American Civil War]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clara_Harris"}
{"title_page": "Rashid Askari", "text_new": "{{Tone|date=April 2020}}\n{{POV|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Bangladeshi writer and academic}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Harun-Ur-Rashid Askari\n| native_name         = \u09b0\u09be\u09b6\u09bf\u09a6 \u0986\u09b8\u0995\u09be\u09b0\u09c0\n| image               = Rashid Askari\n| caption             = \n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1965|06|01}}\n| birth_place         = Askarpur, [[Mithapukur]], [[Rangpur District|Rangpur]], [[East Pakistan]], Present day [[Bangladesh]]\n| office              = [[Vice-Chancellor]] of [[Islamic University, Bangladesh|Islamic University]]\n| term_start          = 21 August 2016\n| nationality         = Bangladeshi\n| occupation          = Writer, fictionist, columnist, university academic, media personality\n| alma_mater          = {{unbulleted list|[[University of Dhaka]]|[[University of Pune]]}}\n| signature           = \u09b0\u09be\u09b6\u09bf\u09a6 \u0986\u09b8\u0995\u09be\u09b0\u09c0\u09b0 \u09b8\u09cd\u09ac\u09be\u0995\u09cd\u09b7\u09b0.png\n}}\n\n'''Harun-Ur-Rashid Askari''' (born 1 June 1965), known as '''Rashid Askari''', is a Bengali-English writer, fictionist, columnist, translator, media personality and an academic in [[Bangladesh]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://themissingslate.com/2015/10/01/a-brief-history-of-bangladeshi-writing-in-english/2/| title= A brief history of Bangladeshi writing in English| publisher=The Missing Slate | date=1 October 2015 | accessdate= 9 July 2017}}</ref> He is the current and the 12th [[vice-chancellor]] of [[Islamic University, Bangladesh]] in [[Kushtia]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://newagebd.net/247604/rashid-askari-made-iu-vc/ | title=Rashid Askari made IU VC | publisher=New Age | date=22 August 2016 | accessdate=25 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nAskari was born in Askarpur, [[Mithapukur]], [[Rangpur District|Rangpur]] in 1965 in erstwhile East Pakistan (now Bangladesh) during a difficult time in the country's history. M. A. Mannan, an English teacher and headmaster, was his father and Setara Begum, a housewife, is his mother. Rashid passed the secondary school and higher secondary certificate examinations in 1980 and 1982 with merit. He \"obtained Honours and Master\u2019s degrees in English from [[Dhaka University]] with distinction, and a PhD in [[Indian English Literature]] from the [[University of Poona]]\".<ref name=\"ds18Sep2016\">{{cite news |title=A Talk with IU VC |url=http://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/167531/A-Talk-with-IU-VC |newspaper=Daily Sun |location=Dhaka |date=18 September 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170306035353/http://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/167531/A-Talk-with-IU-VC |archive-date=6 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nAskari joined [[Islamic University, Bangladesh|Islamic University]], Kushtia as a lecturer in English in 1990. He became a professor in 2005 and was head of the English department more than once. He served with King Khalid University - the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia as a professor of English for five years (2008-2013). Askari later became a writer. He \"debut as a writer was marked in 1996 by his book The Dying Homeland. Until recently, he has authored seven books, and edited three volumes of English Writings of Rabindranath Tagore (2012-2013) published in commemoration of the 150th birth anniversary of the poet. He has also written a large number of articles, essays and newspaper columns on a great variety of themes ranging from national to international and colonial to postcolonial, which have been published at home and abroad\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sangatreview.org/blog/2016/04/30/rashid-askari/|title=Rashid Askari \u2013 Sangat Book Review|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> He was elected the Secretary General of Federation of Bangladesh University Teachers' Association for 2014.<ref>{{cite news |title=Farid made president, Rashid secy gen of FBUTA |url=http://old-archives.newagebd.net/detail.php?date=2014-03-09&nid=86011 |newspaper=New Age |location=Dhaka |agency=BSS |date=9 March 2014}}</ref> He was \"made new chairman of Folklore Studies Department of the university in [[Kushtia District|Kushtia]]\".<ref>{{cite news |title=IU Folklore Dept gets new chairman|url=http://www.thefinancialexpress-bd.com/2016/01/21/11828|newspaper=The Financial Express|location=Dhaka |agency=BSS |date=21 January 2016}}</ref> Askari has been nominated as a part-time member of the University Grants Commission of Bangladesh (UGC).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/434781/Dr-Rashid-Askari-nominated-UGC-parttime-member|title=Dr Rashid Askari nominated UGC part-time member|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref> He is working as a member of \"the international publication and translation sub-committee\" under \"Bangabandhu\u2019s Birth Centenary Celebration National Implementation Committee\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bssnews.net/?p=283009|title=Coffee table book to be published on Bangabandhu {{!}} Bangladesh Sangbad Sangstha (BSS)|last=Mosharrof|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref> and translated Sheikh Mujib's 10 January speech delivered at the Race Course into English.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/supplements/bangabandhus-homecoming-day/news/we-dont-know-defeat-1852090|title='We don't know defeat'|date=2020-01-10|website=The Daily Star|language=en|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\nHe is a peer reviewer and a Quality Assurance (QA) expert nominated by the Quality Assurance Unit of the Government of [[Bangladesh|People's Republic of Bangladesh]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.qau.gov.bd/system/files/reports/Peer%20Reviewers%20panel%20(Bangladesh).pdf |title=Peer Reviewers Panel (QA experts) |website=Quality Assurance Unit, University Grants Commission |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921020121/http://www.qau.gov.bd/system/files/reports/Peer%20Reviewers%20panel%20(Bangladesh).pdf |archive-date=21 September 2016}}</ref> \"...Askari regularly writes columns in various newspapers\"...<ref name=\"ds18Sep2016\" /> \"The areas of his academic interest include Modern and Postmodern Fiction, Colonial and Postcolonial Literatures, South-Asian Writing in English, Literary Theories and Creative Writing\".<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.sangatreview.org/rashid-askari/ | title=Rashid Askari \u2013 Sangat Book Review}}</ref> In the recent past \"Askari has been accorded gold medal for his contribution to advancement of education sector\" in Bangladesh.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/385380|title=Abul Hossain, Askari awarded for contribution to education sector|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dailyasianage.com/news/173438/?regenerate|title=IU VC got PBA gold medal {{!}} The Asian Age Online, Bangladesh|website=The Asian Age|language=en|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref> He has also received \"Janonetri Sheikh Hasina Award 2019\" for his outstanding contribution to education sector,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/printversion/details/427995/IU-VC-awarded-\u2018Jononetri-Sheikh-Hasina-Sommanona-Padak2019\u2019|title=IU VC awarded 'Jononetri Sheikh Hasina Sommanona Padak-2019'|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>  and \"won the Dhaka University Alumni News Award 2020\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://unb.com.bd/category/Bangladesh/iu-vc-wins-du-alumni-news-award/44638|title=IU VC wins DU Alumni News Award|last=Developer)|first=Md Ashequl Morsalin Ibne Kamal(Team Leader){{!}} Niloy Saha(Sr Web Developer){{!}} Shohana Afroz(Web Developer){{!}} Jobayer Hossain(Web|website=unb.com.bd|language=English|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>   \n\n==Writing style==\n\nAskari had a flair for creative writing since his school days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sangatreview.org/blog/2016/04/30/rashid-askari/|title=Rashid Askari \u2013 Sangat Book Review|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> An unsigned profile in ''The Kushtia Times'' stated that Askari writes \"both Bengali and English with equal ease and efficiency\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Profile of the week--Dr. Rashid Askari: Fiction writer, critic, columnist, teacher, and social analyst |url=http://www.thekushtiatimes.com/09/01/2012/profile-of-the-week/ |newspaper=The Kushtia Times |date=9 January 2012}}</ref> Bangladeshi novelist and critic [[Syed Manzoorul Islam]] notes: \"He writes witty, racy stories with surprisingly serious undertones. Picking real-life events from the remote areas and the marginal people of the country and weaving them into various fictional forms are the hallmarks of his storytelling. ... Though not new in a ground-breaking way, his stories are both intense and original. The overall tone of his language is gently sarcastic ...\".<ref>{{cite news |last=Islam |first=Syed Manzoorul |authorlink=Syed Manzoorul Islam |date=16 February 2012 |title=Nineteen seventy one and other stories: a collection of short stories |url=http://www.dhakacourier.com.bd/?p=4899 |newspaper=Dhaka Courier |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130523232442/http://www.dhakacourier.com.bd/?p=4899 |archive-date=23 May 2013}}</ref> \"Dr. Askari has demonstrated enough artistic talent to come up with fiction in English, which must be a source of inspiration for many of us\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daily-sun.com/arcprint/details/167531/A-Talk-with-IU-VC/2016-09-18|title=A Talk with IU VC|website=Daily Sun|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In his short story collection ''Nineteen Seventy One and Other Stories''(2011) \"Rashid Askari speaks of a long-ago war, revisiting the age of brutality we emerged free of through beating back the denizens of darkness\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/opinion/op-ed/2019/08/22/a-chronicler-of-the-human-soul?fbclid=IwAR05ybsYp1fZgPL_slBomUp0ifBBZvZsLx4CIqHWzZpH6dwOq9V5pwAgubI|title=A chronicler of the human soul|date=2019-08-22|website=Dhaka Tribune|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> The book has been translated into [[French language|French Language]] and also into [[Hindi]]\"'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bangladeshpost.net/iu-vcs-book-translated-into-french|title=IU VC's book translated into French|last=Desk|first=BD Post|date=2018-12-01|website=A Daily with a Difference {{!}} Latest Online English Daily among Bangladesh Newspapers|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-06}}</ref>.''' ''His story \"''The Disclosure''\"'' was published in the emerging and seasoned writers publishing platform Kitaab'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kitaab.org/2019/10/12/short-story-the-disclosure/|title=Short Story: The Disclosure|last=Chakravarty|first=Mitali|date=2019-10-12|website=kitaab|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref> Another story \"The virgin whore\" was published in  the [[New York City|New York]] City and [[India]] based magazine Cafe Dissensus''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cafedissensusblog.com/2019/03/31/short-story-the-virgin-whore/|title=Short Story: The virgin whore|last=WordPress.com|first=Blog at|date=2019-03-31|website=Cafe Dissensus Everyday|language=en|access-date=2019-10-17}}</ref>''. His short story \"Virus''\"'' was published in the Daily Sun's Eid Special 2017 and \u201cA slice of sky\u201d has been published in the Contemporary Literary Review India (CLRI), a peer-reviewed , internationally refereed and high impact factor journal.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Askari|first=Dr Rashid|date=2019-11-05|title=A Slice of Sky|url=https://literaryjournal.in/index.php/clri/article/view/385|journal=Contemporary Literary Review India|language=en|volume=6|issue=4|pages=68\u201391|issn=2394-6075}}</ref> \"Sharp and minute detailed description of human behaviour, and pictorial presentation of events and settings in his carefully chosen words demonstrate Rashid Askari\u2019s mastery in story writing/telling,\" says the President of the International Consortium for Social Development and Professor of Social Work at Charles Sturt University, NSW, Australia, Dr. Manohar Pawar.'''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pawar|first=Manohar|date=2019-12-01|title=Askari Rashid, Nineteen Seventy One: Short Stories.|journal=The International Journal of Community and Social Development|language=en|volume=1|issue=4|pages=357\u2013358|doi=10.1177/2516602619889245|issn=2516-6026}}</ref>'''\n\n==Works==\n=== Books ===\n* {{cite book |last=Askari |first=Rashid |year=1996 |script-title=bn:\u09ae\u09c1\u09ae\u09c2\u09b0\u09cd\u09b7\u09c1 \u09b8\u09cd\u09ac\u09a6\u09c7\u09b6 |trans-title=The Dying Homeland |location=Dhaka |language=bn}}  \n* {{cite book |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |year=1996 | script-title=bn:\u0987\u09a8\u09cd\u09a6\u09cb-\u0987\u0982\u09b0\u09c7\u099c\u09bf \u09b8\u09be\u09b9\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09af \u0993 \u0985\u09a8\u09cd\u09af\u09be\u09a8\u09cd\u09af|trans-title= Indo-English Literature and Others|location=Dhaka |language=bn}}\n* {{cite book |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |year=1997 |script-title=bn:\u098f\u0995\u09be\u09b2\u09c7\u09b0 \u09b0\u09c2\u09aa\u0995\u09a5\u09be|trans-title=Today's Folktale|location=Dhaka |language=bn}}\n* {{cite book |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |year=2001 |script-title=bn:\u09ac\u09bf\u09a8\u09bf\u09b0\u09cd\u09ae\u09bf\u09a4 \u09ad\u09be\u09ac\u09a8\u09be |trans-title=Deconstructing Thoughts |location=Dhaka |language=bn}}\n* {{cite book |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 |year=2002 |script-title=bn:\u0989\u09a4\u09cd\u09a4\u09b0\u09be\u09a7\u09c1\u09a8\u09bf\u0995 \u09b8\u09be\u09b9\u09bf\u09a4\u09cd\u09af \u0993 \u09b8\u09ae\u09be\u09b2\u09cb\u099a\u09a8\u09be \u09a4\u09a4\u09cd\u09a4\u09cd\u09ac |trans-title=Postmodern Literary and Critical Theory |location=Dhaka |language=bn}}\n* {{cite book |last=Askari |first=Rashid |author-mask=2 